<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<img border=0 width=43 height=43 src="../../images/class1.gif">
</td>

<td valign=middle width=440>
<center><h3>
Attacks on Personal Information
</h3>
</center><BR>
<p>December 13, 1996</p>


<p align="center"><b>                     SECOND INTERNATIONAL CONFERENCE<BR>
                         ON INFORMATION WARFARE<BR>
                                                       
                  Chaos on the Electronic Superhighway<BR>
                                      
                            JANUARY 18, 1995<BR>
                                                                      
                            MONTREAL, QUEBEC<BR>
                                                                        
                               BRIAN FORAN<BR>
                                    
                             Special Advisor<BR>

     </b></p>

<P>     The subject of privacy has emerged, of late, as one of the hot buttons of public
debate on the information highway.  Stories about electronic medical record
networks, interception of racy voice mail messages and hackers on the INTERNET
are focussing people's attention on their privacy.  But the electronic highway is
only one illustration of the uneasy relationship between privacy and technology. 
Dealing with that potential conflict demands that we first address the technological
context in which we find ourselves.

<P>     So I'd like to give you first a glimpse of some studies on the impact of
technology on society at large.  I'll also refer to some specific studies and surveys
on technology and individual privacy and the problems these identified.  And finally,
I'd like to mention some observations from our office's perspective and our concern
that a specific privacy framework may be necessary to begin building some
defences against information warfare. 

<P>     I had the privilege recently of hearing Frank Ogden, that wonderfully engaging
futurist from Vancouver.  What Mr. Ogden had to say, however, did not comfort
me because in his opinion there is no longer any privacy in our present
technological age and there would certainly be none in the future.  Our lives, he
claimed, are open books to anyone with the wits, desire, and technology to read
them.  

<P>     For example, he mentioned, several years ago, he had obtained, through
technological means, the KGB desk books on all US foreign intelligence activities --
but not to worry, he said, because, six months prior to that, he had already
obtained the US President's briefing books on those same issues.  

<P>     So anecdote aside, according to Ogden, there are no secrets in the age of
technology and there are no borders.  Conventional political frontiers are obsolete
and laws can provide little protection, indeed, present no obstacle, moral or
otherwise, to those who will use technology to enter any database or
communications systems for pleasure or gain.   

<P>     Now as much as I admire Mr. Ogden, and it's hard not to be a great fan of his,
it seems to me that the rapture of technology has so mesmerized him that perhaps
he has neglected other equally meaningful and significant interests.  By striving to
be one with the technology, he has perhaps swung the balance to an extreme and,
while his point of view may be valid, the other extreme or at least other
considerations demand our attention.


<P>     I mention Mr. Ogden simply to emphasize the nature of two competing and
strikingly divergent views on the question of technology.  One view claims that
technology should be driving the changes that are taking place in information
management and communications processes and that we should simply hang on
for the ride.  The other suggests that technology simply offers us choices and that
human values should direct the changes that technology offers us.

<P>     In discussing these divergent views and the impact of technology on our lives, I
should mention the work of Neil Postman whose l992 book entitled Technopoly will
likely become one of the landmark studies in the field.

<P>     His thesis, simply stated, is that we are in danger of becoming what he calls a
"Technopoly", a system in which technology of every kind is cheerfully granted
sovereignty over all aspects of our lives.  He argues that while technologies are
indispensable to our lives, we must understand and control them and place them in
the context of our larger human goals, our social values, and our national
intentions.  

<P>     As well, he says, when we admit a new technology (something like the
INTERNET) into our culture, we must do so with our eyes open.  Often the
discoverer of an art or innovation is not the best judge of the good or harm that will
accrue to those who use it.

<P>     Postman also points out that technological change is not additive or subtractive
-- it is ecological.  By that he means that one significant change generates total
environmental change.  To cite an example from nature, if we remove all of a
species from an environment, we are not left with the same environment minus
that species; we have a new environment because we have reconstituted the
conditions of existence.

<P>     In the same way, a new technology does not simply add or subtract -- it
changes everything.  For example, fifty years after the invention of the printing
press, we did not have the same old Europe plus the printing press.  We had an
entirely different Europe.  Likewise after television, we did not have the same old
society plus television, we had an entirely different society.

<P>     So it is not enough, in Postman's view, simply to consider whether
communications will be more effective on electronic highways, or whether
information exchanges will be better supported on fully connected systems.  That
only brings an immediate, practical answer, and one which may deter us from
asking ourselves what other serious human and social impacts may result from the
new technology.  In building this highway, this network of networks, what changes
may we be causing to our social environment, to our human ecology?

<P>     Obviously, it is a mistake to assume that every technological change or
innovation has a one-sided effect, either good or bad.  Every technology is probably
both a blessing and a curse.  My point in raising the thoughts of Postman is simply
that we are all of us caught up in being zealots for technology wondering what
technology can do, but not reflecting on what it can undo.  

<P>     We must recognize and consider what has been poetically termed as the
"intimations of deprival".  That is, those hints and indications of what's being lost,
or what voices and values are being silenced, and then question the underlying
assumptions in the trade-offs.

<P>     Now what does all of this have to do with privacy?  Well, for many years
scholars have been considering the impact of technology on privacy.  Privacy, as
we define it, is simply the right of the individual to control the flow of information
about oneself, the right to fair, reasonable and confidential information practices. 
This claim of informational privacy assumes that all information about an individual
is fundamentally his or her property to communicate or withhold as desired -- it is
the democratic notion of self-determination or autonomy which, in the case of
information, dictates that no one should have more control over a person's
information than the person.

<P>     But the more that can be known about a person, the less that person's
autonomy.  And these days, in an information society, our individual autonomy and
our sense of control are on the line.  That is the heart of the privacy problem and
that is why privacy has become such an emotionally-charged issue.

<P>     The federal government has attempted to deal with this issue by enacting the
Privacy Act, a somewhat misleading name.  Privacy Commissioner Bruce Phillips
once joked that it might be more accurate to call it "an act respecting the
protection of personal information in the hands of Ottawa bureaucrats".  The office
and the position of Privacy Commissioner were created in 1983 basically to serve
an ombuds role to investigate complaints under the Privacy Act.  

<P>     The act is essentially data protection legislation, designed to control the
collection, retention, use, disclosure and protection of personal information.  It is
similar to most of those in effect in major Western countries.

<P>     At its heart, the federal Privacy Act is an "information handlers code of ethics".

<P>It is a code of fair information principles which recognizes the inherent right of
ownership of the information by the people from whom it was taken.  It requires
government to collect data directly from those people wherever possible.  It obliges
government to tell people why the information is needed and how it will be used. 
It imposes obligations on government to protect that data from unauthorized or
unrelated uses and disclosures.  It gives individuals the right to examine their
information.  And finally, it puts in place an independent ombudsman (our office) to
resolve problems and oversee compliance.

<P>     The law and thus our office's authority extend only to Canadian federal
government institutions (150 or so).  We have no jurisdiction (other than the purely
moral) over the provincial, municipal or private sectors.

<P>     As it stands, however, the label has encouraged Canadians to think of the
federal Privacy Commissioner as the guardian of every aspect of their privacy
rights.  They complain to us if they are denied information which they have
requested, or if they feel that a government department is collecting, keeping, or
misusing their information in a way that contravenes the act.  Since 1983, we
have investigated approximately 10,000 such complaints.

<P>     As well, people call and write us about anything that touches on their personal
privacy.  This can include junk mail, social insurance numbers, credit card
applications, video surveillance, and cross border shopping.  Recently, these calls
and letters run to more than 8000 a year. Since 1983, we have handled over
30,000 such inquiries.

<P>     We also audit government compliance to the act by examining  government
departments and how they manage their personal information holdings.  Finally, we
try to sensitize the public to privacy issues.   For example, in the past four years,
we have issued major studies dealing with the privacy implications of Drug Testing,
AIDS, and Genetic Testing.  We have also responded to Industry Canada's paper
on Privacy on the Canadian Information Highway.

<P>     At present, the majority of Canadian governments have privacy laws which
control government collection, use and disclosure of personal data and which give
individuals the right to see their own personal information.

<P>     However, the studies so far have concluded that dramatic advances in
telecommunications and information technology change the relationship between
individuals and government.  New technologies are able to deal with personal
information faster, new electronic highways will deliver that personal information
and link it more extensively, and cheaper than ever before.  

     
 <P>    The result is a growing vulnerability of information and the consequent loss of
privacy -- losses that some argue are the inevitable trade-offs against this greater
speed, efficiency, and cost-effectiveness.  Privacy is often at the top of the list of
rights to be traded off for other perceived benefits, usually because it's not
recognized as an issue until it's lost.  But once lost, there is no remedy -- you can't
get it back, it's gone.  

<P>     So we are tempted with technology's benefits but we often overlook its
vulnerabilities.  And that leads me, finally, to the topic of this panel, attacks on
personal information.  

<P>     Perhaps I should begin by asking whether anyone care that personal information
may be under attack.  Well, Canadians do care.  A comprehensive 1993 Canadian
survey of public attitudes towards privacy (financed by a consortium of private and
public sector organizations) revealed a "pervasive sense that personal privacy is
under seige" -- 52 per cent were "extremely concerned", and about 90 percent
were at least moderately concerned over their personal privacy.  

<P>     In other words, as a contemporary issue, it is right up there with such issues as
unemployment and the environment, and actually ahead of national unity.

<P>     The survey also revealed that, beyond generalities, the public doesn't know a
lot about this issue but that where it does understand a specific matter, it has no
trouble rendering a verdict.  I give you cellular telephones as an example.  Most
people know that such devices can be monitored.  Seventy-seven percent of people
surveyed were in favour of measures to protect the privacy of such
communications; eighty-three percent did not believe that anyone should record
any private cellular phone conversations for any reason.

<P>     But what the survey revealed most dramatically was the existence in the public
of a deep sense of unease:  an awareness that advanced technologies (and those
that use them) are impinging on their lives in ways they don't yet understand; and
a desire to know more and to have much more control and personal involvement in
the decision-making process.

<P>     A later survey, conducted by Gallop for Anderson Consulting, found that almost
84 per cent of Canadians were worried about their privacy on the information
highway.  Anderson was surprised at the high level of concern, one it described as
high enough to stop highway construction in its tracks.



<P>     What seems to be clear in all of this is that the major problems that will arise
will not be related to the technology itself but with how well we are able to
consider the implications of the technology on those human values such as privacy.

<P>It will also determine whether the public will be willing participants -- or will mount
the barricades.

<P>     And this brings me finally to the topic of Information Warfare and the argument
so powerfully presented by Winn Schwartau in his provocative book.  Mr.
Schwartau argues that in the new world order, there will be no such thing as
electronic privacy, that everything we do will be recorded somewhere in a digital
repository, and that those records which define us as individuals will be
unprotected, subject to malicious modification, unauthorized disclosure and
out-and-out destruction.  

<P>     In short, we are at war.  Cyberspace is the battlefield and we are under a
virtual attack (Class 1 Information Warfare) in which we will be subjected to
something akin to terrorism against our digital privacy, the electronic essence of
our lives.  

<P>     Schwartau argues that the first Information Warriors in Cyberspace are hackers.

<P>In this new world order, hackers rule.  They know far more about computers and
how to manipulate them than the public ever will.  And their goal is to rule the
global electronic data superhighways of the future.    

<P>     Well, if this is a war, we should take the advice given over 25 centuries ago by
Asian war master Sun Tzu who said "Know the enemy - if ignorant of the enemy,
you are certain to be in peril".  

<P>     So who are these hackers?  Robin Hoods, as portrayed by the tabloid press? 
Most experts characterize them as socially inadequate young males.  Caroline
Osborn, a British Crown Prosecutor, who has long pursued and prosecuted
computer criminals and hackers, has come to regard them as "stupid little nerds
who have not yet discovered girls and beer".

<P>     Winn Schwartau seems to agree with the fact that present day hackers
 are: </P>

     -    mostly misfit males between twelve and twenty-eight<BR>
     -    smart but did lousy in school<BR>
     -    come from dysfunctional families<BR>
     
<P>     In short, guys who are basically misunderstood and can't get a date.

<P>     Our moderator, Dr. Kabay, has expanded that definition to further suggest that,
among other things, hackers are characterized by:</P>

     -    a grandiose sense of self-importance<BR>
     -    a preoccupation with fantasies of unlimited success<BR>
     -    a need for constant attention and admiration<BR>
     -    strong negative responses to threats to self-esteem
          feelings of entitlement<BR>
     -    interpersonal exploitiveness<BR>
     -    alternate feelings of overidealization and devaluation<BR>
     -    a lack of empathy.<BR>
     
<P>     Bruce Sterling, in his 1992 book, "The Hacker Crackdown" estimated the
hacker population at about 5000 people.  Of these, he guessed that as few as a
hundred are truly "elite" - active computer intruders, skilled enough to penetrate
sophisticated systems and  to be truly worrisome to corporate security and law
enforcement.  He also disputes the theory that hackers exist in vast swarms and
will soon dominate the cybernetic universe. 

<P>     Does this mean that we can ignore the threat?   No, because, obviously, the
so-called digital underground is not homogeneous - we have Inner city hackers
without conscience -- arrogant, disdainful, and alienated.  For the disenfranchised,
cyberspace is the only place where they have power and can make the rules.  

<P>     And then there are the Eurohackers - apparently the Netherlands has the
world's best hackers.  To them, hacking is simply beating technology.  Breaking
into a computer should not be a crime, they argue, although hurting people with
the data or hurting the systems should be illegal. 

<P>     So what is the truth about hacking and hackers?  Everything seems to point to
the conclusion that hackers are just kids, no matter what their age.  On the other
hand, they are kids with goals and weapons.  Their goals involve:

<P>1.   Theft of information and services (corporate secrets, military secrets, calling    

cards and electronic money devices) 

<P>2.   Modification of information (altering financial credit, medical records etc.)

<P>3.   Destruction of information and information systems.

<P>     Their weapons in cyberspace are almost invisible; their code of ethics is
inconsistent; they believe that their anarchy can be tolerated in cyberspace
because most other people act responsibly.

<P>     Whatever the profile, hackers have shown the chinks in the armour - if kids can
do such damage, what about dedicated, well-financed, perhaps mercenary
professionals?

<P>     So will the hacker threat evolve in that manner as technology evolves.  Some
paint a scary picture of terrorist info-criminals, attacking computer networks, the
vulnerable nervous system of modern society.  They suggest that the hacker
community is becoming more sophisticated and organized.  Will they become
international gangs of criminals who steal data, destroy systems and divert funds?  

<P>     Others state that no evidence exists that the current generation of hackers is
attempting to sabotage entire networks, although there is some evidence that the
newest generation of hackers may be more motivated by personal gain than the
traditional ethic of sheer curiosity.  

<P>     And what about subversives launching sporadic attacks on the information
superhighway; electronic invaders compromising passwords, stealing data,
monitoring telephone calls and gathering personal data on individuals.

<P>     Two alleged underground groups of hackers deserve mention: the Legion of
Doom (20 members around the USA) and the Masters of Deception (five members
aged 18-22).  The Legion of Doom used pilfered passwords and old identification
cards to gain access to computers at BellSouth and eavesdropped on
conversations, rerouted calls, etc.  The Masters of Deception broke into computers
at TRW and Nynex where they stole credit reports and confidential information that
were sold to private investigators.

<P>     The Masters of Deception were indicted for their crimes in 1992 but, according
to their most infamous member, Phiber Optic, there really was no such group and
no computer underground and certainly he had never been involved in any
organized fashion.

<P>     So are hackers, or rather Crackers, the more malevolent hackers, the terrorists
of the Information Age?  According to the foremost American expert on terrorism,
the answer is, "No".  We do not find these villains of the information age in the
ranks of today's terrorists.  Brian Michael Jenkins (Deputy Chairman of Kroll
Associates and a global expert on terrorism and its impact on the future - speaking
in OMNI November 1994) says that he does not see terrorists innovating much
with tactics.  It is not a matter of terrorists moving into the domain of computer
crime.  Politically motivated hackers might move towards terrorism but they don't
seem to be drawn by ideological causes.  And terrorists do not go out and recruit
computer literates; conspiracies, according to Jenkins, do not work that way.    
     
<P>     As well, if we accept that the characteristics of an industrial age war can be
described as large armies, several separated theatres of operation, joint operations
and relatively modern technologies, then the Information Warfare model as
presented does not meet this definition, although one could suggest it does involve
several separated theatres of operation and unquestionably modern technology.

<P>     Let me tell you of my recent vicarious foray into the sketchy world of hackers.

<P>     I obtained copies of 2600 - The Hacker Quarterly, and the Hacker Chronicles - a
CD ROM - as well as investigated the "alt. hacker" bulletin boards on the
INTERNET.

<P>     2600, the Hacker Quarterly, generally features a series of articles under various
pseudonyms.  Even the publisher goes by the fictitious name of Emmanuel
Goldstein, the character Orwell used as his political mouthpiece against omnipotent
government in the novel "1984".

<P>     As well, the reader will be forgiven if he or she was not able to actually read or
understand the magazine.  To paraphrase John Perry Barlow, it is a thing of
surpassing opacity.   And anyone who can fully understand it has probably altered
his consciousness sufficiently to preclude ever again reading Shakespeare, Blake, or
even Bob Dylan.  

<P>     Whether these articles actually help anyone break into computer systems, I can
only speculate.  Some people have suggested to me that anyone stupid enough to
try what is published in these magazines deserves whatever legal or other
consequence is likely to befall him.  

<P>     Recent articles include:

<P>     "Cordless Fun" -- how to legally monitor people on their cordless phones and    

   listing frequencies of AT & T models,  
     
<P>     "Admin without a Clue"-- claiming 40 percent of the passwords on the 
computer science system have been cracked - primarily due to arrogance of 
system operators not admitting that a security problem could exist;
     
<P>     "Hacking Prodigy" -- describes how to get a month's free service on Prodigy.

<P>     Who reads these articles?  In June, I noticed two copies of the summer issue
displayed at my local magazine stand.  In November, the same two copies were
still on display, plus two copies of the Autumn issue.  I bought a copy of each. 
This past weekend, the remaining two copies were still on display 
     
<P>     My surfing the INTERNET found widespread distribution of intrusion tool kits,
the hacker's equivalent of the burglar's black bag.  The tool kits contain programs
that purport to listen to conversations between computers on the network; they
will gain illicit entry into computers to look for valuable data or to shut the
computer down - to learn and copy passwords and access codes to get unlimited
access - and to listen to private E-mail between users.

<P>     Do  we believe there are hackers everywhere?  If we allow any kind of external
connection, there is the potential for hackers to attack our networks.  But does the
real problem lie elsewhere?

<P>     Hackers don't have any magic tricks to get into our systems - they simply
capitalize on our system's weakness.  If we have weak passwords, they'll guess
them by repeated trial and error.  And if we have no intruder detection system on
our networks, we'll never even know that they're trying to get in. 

<P>     But we do have the tools and technology to defeat the Information Warrior. 
The question is, "Why have we done so little?"  The answer could be arrogance,
apathy, or ignorance.

<P>     The message here is not that electronic privacy is an oxymoron -- the message
is that we must become more responsible for the systems we put in place.  System
compromise is often the result of our sloppiness or inattention.  Sure clever
electronic intrusions take place but the intrusions are made possible because the
users either don't understand or won't accept their responsibilities to protect
privacy and confidentiality.

<P>     We must take this stuff seriously - if we don't take due care, the alacrity and
ease of penetration is likely to be everyone's worst nightmare, as described by Mr.
Schwartau.
     
<P>     We need to have robust external controls, audit trails, authorization, and
attributable entries,  We need to create disincentives for those who have the 
inclination to hack:  disincentives like firewalls over all systems connected to the
INTERNET; disincentives like monitoring traffic in and out of our systems to see
who is snooping around looking for passwords.

<P>     I suggest we can dispose of the myth of the smart hacker because that myth
excuses us from limiting connections or avoiding the effort of building robust and
thorough security.  Penetration is not the hackers success;  penetration is more
likely our failure to erect proper systems defence.

<P>     And the first defence should be on raising the level of awareness.  Now people
have a right not to care about their personal information.  If they want to
voluntarily relinquish control over their own personal information to others, that is
their right.  But they must make that decision based on clear information.  And
no-one has the right to compromise their duty of care and confidentiality over the
personal records of others.

<P>     Mich Kabay suggests that criminal hacking is a social problem not merely a
technical issue.  I tend to agree with him when he says that all of us should be
reaching out to educate young people about the rules of network usage - we have
to extend the rules of morality and civility - of respect and communication - into
cyberspace.  
     
<P>     We are all of us bound together by norms, rules and values, even when these
are only implicitly understood, sometimes conflicting and often impaired.  Our lives
are both secured in society and connected to each other by this ethical "glue".

<P>     But technology has brought us into the Information Age, in some ways, without
much contemplation of the social responsibilities involved.  As was typical, the
technologies preceded the development of ethics.  And thus, we have the issues of
hacking, unauthorized access into private, personal computer files, systems pranks,
and vandalism, software piracy, electronic harassment, and bulletin boards of hate,
pornography and violence.

<P>     It seems we sometimes suffer from a stunning inability to place the pursuit of
human dignity at the heart of our development and progress.  It is fairly obvious
that the uses of technology are largely determined by the framework in which they
are developed.  All infrastructures could have been designed differently if the initial
design priority had been human rather than technological development.

<P>     So is there is no such thing as electronic privacy?  I am far too optimistic to
agree that there is no privacy in the electronic age or that information cannot be
kept private -- there is and it can.  One means that I envisage to accomplish that is
a scenario in which  there is a convergence of disciplines between the privacy and
security communities.  Let me explain.


  <P>   For many, "privacy", "confidentiality" and "security" come down to the same
thing -- safeguarding information.  In fact, each term has a meaning distinct from
the others.  To understand the issues raised by each, it is essential to understand
those distinctions.

<P>     Privacy (in an information context) concerns an individual right, our right as
individuals to control the flow of our personal information.

<P>     Confidentiality is an obligation of an organization to protect the personal
information with which it has been entrusted.  It is a fiduciary duty, a duty of care
to maintain the secrecy of the information.

<P>     And finally, security is the process of assessing the threats and risks posed to
information and taking the appropriate steps to keep the information safe from
harm.  

<P>     Where does that leave us in our quest to devise rules for information flows on
the information highway?  

<P>     First, we should recognize that privacy (a right), confidentiality (a duty) and
security (a process), while distinct, are complementary and offer a mosaic of
approaches to deal with the challenges we face.  All players will have to commit to
honouring the same fundamental information practices.  We must devise principles
to balance what is at stake.  Professionals in all three disciplines have a unique
combination of skills and experience which they can bring together to construct
solutions.
   
<P>     If we can clearly define the rights and the responsibilities of individuals,
corporate bodies and governments and make the whole process transparent, we
might be able to deal openly and intelligently with the issues facing us.  In all of
this, there is an absence so far of an appropriate legislative and regulatory
framework.  The Office of the Privacy Commissioner feels that one is urgently
needed.

<P>     Here, for discussion, are the kind of principles we would like to see in law to
protect privacy, confidentiality and security:
     
<P>     * A reasonable expectation of information privacy is fundamental to the   
provision, use and regulation of information systems.
     
<P>     * An assessment of the privacy impact of current or planned activities should  
be conducted before collecting or transacting personal data.
     

<P>     * An adherence by organizations to a fair information code such as the Privacy 
Act governing collection, use, disclosure, disposal and security.

<P>As well, organizations should:

<P>     * develop administrative procedures to ensure the integrity of personal   
information, that it is accurate, timely, complete and relevant to the purposes     
for which it is collected;
     
<P>     * establish technological procedures to protect the reliability and integrity of
electronic communications through encryption, smart cards and other tools;
     
<P>     * establish a human security procedure to ensure accountability for the system;
     

<P>improper use of their personal information.

<BR>


</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
