<IMG ALT="[Bomb2]" SRC="../../images/bomb2_li.gif" width=580><p>


<!-- Article Body Table ---------------------------------------------->

<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<img border=0 width=43 height=43 src="../../images/class1.gif">
</td>
<td valign=middle width=440>
<center><h3>
NJ Genetic Privacy Bill   ----  DNA data is a hot topic!
</h3>
</center>
November 26, 1996<BR>

<P>Based upon an Associated Press story published in The Trenton Times
(Trenton, NJ) as "New law shields DNA data"; Wed, 20 Nov 1996, p. A6.

<P>On Tuesday, 19 Nov 1996, New Jersey Governor Christine Whitman signed the NJ
Genetic Privacy Act into law. The law prohibits employers or insurance
companies from discriminating based upon a person genetic data. New Jersey
became the eight state in the US to adopt such a law.

<P>The law says that no one may obtain a person's genetic information without
the person's consent and that the DNA samples must be destroyed promptly
when the person requests the destruction. The law specifies fines up to
$5,000 and jail term for the unauthorized disclosure of the DNA information.
Insurance companies and employers who use DNA data to discriminate against a
person can face up to $5,000 in fines for each offense.

<P>The NJ Genetic Privacy Act was enacted out of concerns that genetic tests
for things such as susceptibility to breast cancer and other diseases could
be used by insurers and employers to deny coverage or employment opportunities.

<P>The bill's prime sponsor, NJ State Senator Jack Sinagra (R-Middlesex
County), "The Genetic Privacy will ensure that our citizens can take
advantage of the advances in genetic testing without the fear of
exploitation or discrimination. This opens up a myriad of opportunities for
new treatments and cures, but it also opens the door for potential abuse."

<P>Governor Whitman had vetoed an earlier version of the bill in September
because it contained a clause stating that one owns one's own genetic
information.  Whitman was concerned that asserting such property rights
would discourage biotech industries from working in New Jersey.  (One
scenario revolving around this concern was of a biotech company developing a
saleable product from information derived from somebody's DNA samples and
the person insists upon royalties.)

<P>------------------------------------------------------------
<P>Other Notes (This is a mental core dump concerning anything even remotely
related to genetic information issues.):  

<P>The issue of genetic privacy is a new field.  I don't believe that this new
law will do all that much, at least not until some significant tests of the
law.  Although the new law will prevent open discrimination, there is the
likelihood that many discrimination cases will be hidden under false claims.

<P>The law does not affect, to my knowledge the use of genetic data by the police.

<P>In the US military, there have been several recent courtmartials concerning
the refusal to submit to DNA sample collections.  A few months ago, the
Village Voice carried an article about two servicemen who refused to submit
to the sampling.  The case was treated as a classic "refusal to carry out
lawful orders".  From the Village Voice article, it looks a big factor in
the cases was the way that the military sought to collect the samples.  It
was done "we'll take swabs of [epithelial] cells from the inside of your
cheek, no and-ifs or buts".  A couple of servicemen objected to the sampling
when the sample takers would not or could not answer their questions about
the use of the samples.  Reportedly, the main purpose of the  samples was to
provide a good method of identifying human remains. But, it is easy for
people to extrapolate many other uses for the data, including the permanent
inclusion of the data in Federal records (just as much as the fingerprints
remain on file forever). If anybody is interested in a better summary of the
Village Voice article  or a photocopy of it, let me know. 

<P>In a recent Wired issue, the military and genetic information was mentioned
in a article about biological research for future warfare and a conference
about it given at the US Army War College.  Now, this item is very much
speculative and sounds like science fiction.  One of the concepts being
considered by some researchers is the development of genetic weapons that
could be used to "take out the next Hitler".  That is, a genetic "bullet"
(e.g.; a custom virus) that would be designed to be lethal to one person on
earth or maybe a handful of people sharing strong genetic similarities.
Again, this is still a ways off and it is an intense example but it gives an
idea of some directions in which the genetic revolution can go.

<P>Other genetic information possibilities are raised in a book review of
_Queer Science_ in the November/December 1996 issue of The Sciences (pp.
34-38). One of the controversies over research concerning homosexuality and
genetic factors for it is the possibility that if a "gay gene" is
discovered, societies and individuals might react in drastic ways.  For
example, parents discovering that their unborn child has the "gay gene"
might opt to abort. Or that the "gay gene" might be interpreted as leading
to certain physiological developments and some people would seek to use
medical treatments to alter these developments.  (The review mentioned that
back in the 1920's, there were some attempts to "cure" homosexuality by
surgery .)

<P>About a decade or two ago, there was some controversy over how to handle
"super males", males with an extra Y chromosome.  XYY males were deemed to
be prone to violence.  This raised the question of using genetic screening
to check for this trait and, then if it is found, of using special care to
prevent violence. Elsewhere, there were studies among the Hutterite
communities concerning depression and suicide that suggested genetic
patterns contributing to this.  (The Hutterites are a religious sections
*roughly* similar to the Amish.)  If a "depression gene" is found, this
could lead to better preventative medicine, to enforced therapies or to
discrimination.  One possible scenario could be employment conditions that
require medical monitoring and advance treatments for certain conditions
deemed to be found in genetic testing.</P>

<BR>
J.D. Abolins<BR>
<a href="jda-ir@pluto.njcc.com">jda-ir@pluto.njcc.com</a><BR>

<P>PS. As usual with my Infolaw mailings, this email is supplied as general
information and opinion.  It is not to be used as substitute for competant
legal counsel in your jurisdiction.</P>

<BR>


</td>

