<td valign=middle width=440>
<center><h2>
Information Revolutions, National Security and Individual Consciousness: Changing Paradigms

</h2>
</center>
 
<BR>

<BR>
<P>
by Elin Whitney-Smith, Ph.D.
<P>
Institute for Change and Learning
<P>
George Washington University
<H2>Assertions/ Observations</H2>

<P>
Every Information Revolution has changed the world in dramatic
ways:
<P>
&#183; how people define themselves
<P>
&#183; definitions of gender 
<P>
&#183; the size and definition of what constitutes a family
<P>
&#183; the size of the political unit
<P>
&#183; what nation is the dominant nation
<P>
&#183; what constitutes National Security 
<P>
&#183; what people are willing to fight and die for.
<H3>Introduction: The Problem</H3>

<P>
We are experiencing what some have called a crisis of will and
others a loss of patriotism. War has become a spectator sport.
We need to ask basic questions. Instead we are pursuing a policy
of &quot;reaction to CNN&quot;. If we see poverty, boat people,
suffering we want to go in a fix it.  However, if we see Americans
being killed we want to pull out.
<P>
The nature of what constitutes a threat has changed.  We can be
brought to the bargaining table by floods of poverty stricken
refugees besieging Miami.  It happened with Haiti and again with
Cuba.  Any country that wants to bargain with the US can play
on our xenophobia by sending us boatloads of their sick and poor.
This is a complete reversal of the ordinary power equation. 
<P>
As individuals, we are feeling increasingly insecure. It is not
limited to Americans. More and more people are being challenged
by their contact with a global world at the same time as the divergence
between the haves and have nots increases. These things combine
to increase fears. Both rich and poor become more likely to listen
to, would be, demagogues who call for a return to the old ways;
to societies defined by ethnic and religious values. The rich
listen because they see the old values supporting stability and
therefore being good for business and the poor listen because
they feel cheated and frightened and see change as an abandonment
of the old ways. Both groups are looking for security and yet
supporting causes which increase instability.
<P>
All of these problems stem from the Information Revolution. Because
an information revolution creates a totally new world. A world
in which the old solutions don't fit. So we shrug our shoulders
and think nothing can be done.
<P>
If we stay in a &quot;do nothing&quot; state of helplessness it
will be dangerous for our country and for peaceful orderly society.
We need to understand the dynamics of an information based society.

<P>
We must leave the default position of letting CNN determine our
foreign policy.  We need to begin conversations that ask the basic
questions.  Questions like: What is national security in a global
information world?  What is a nation in a world where information
crosses boundaries instantaneously and the largest entity is a
trans national information entity - the Internet?  How can we
begin to address global problems including but not limited to
security (e.g. environmental problems) 
<P>
And, we must change the perceptual paradigms of much of the non-western
world. We wage an information war which will facilitate their
entrance into the global information world.  It is this task I
want to address here.
<H3>Individualism vs. Nationalism</H3>

<P>
People in the western world have a different notion of the importance
of individual than do people in other parts of the world.  That
notion of the individual has been the source of both our incredible
wealth and strength and is the reason we now have a &quot;crisis
or will&quot; - we perceive each individual as unique and are
unwilling to have them die.
<P>
For example, think about Scott O'Grady - American hero.  The story
of his ordeal and rescue have become an important part of American
heroic history.  Now, let us imagine for a moment, what we would
have felt if he was not rescued.  Then all the media attention
would have been focused on how his friends and family felt at
his loss. It difficult if not impossible for us to fight a war
with such an individualized focus.  We do not just see heroes
home and happy we also see body bags.
<P>
I assert that this focus on the individual, which has reached
it's culmination in our country today, has historical, traceable
roots.  If we understand the root causes and the dynamic through
which it operates we can use that knowledge as an offensive weapon
in an information war to change the perceptual space of the peoples
of the world. It is the only strategy to prevent tomorrow's Bosnias.
<H3>The Evolution of the Individual</H3>

<P>
The evolution of the individual is based on the separation of
the major information provider from the political power structure.
In the west this began with the fall of the Roman Empire.  It
uncoupled the church (the information provider) from the political
structure. The Church had the right of direct taxation - tithing.
 Tithing made it an advantage to the church for the laity to be
economically productive. Therefore it was to the church's advantage
to foster the development of technology and the spread of information.
 monasteries of the Middle Ages often functioned as agricultural
extension centers do today, to develop and spread information
about techniques and technologies to increase productivity.  
<P>
In contrast, the Eastern Church was closely allied with the Byzantine
Empire.  Its financial existence was dependent on the political
power structure.  It developed a Christianity which supported
mysticism, asceticism and submission to the will of God instead
of good works.  Therefore the Eastern Church did not spread knowledge
to the laity it kept as a trump card in its relationship with
the empire.
<H3>The Press</H3>

<P>
The most powerful entities of the late Middle Ages, in west, were
the cities of Italy and the Iberian peninsula who were in closest
contact with the major information provider - the Church. The
press ushered in a new information age and changed the economic,
political and social structure of the continent.
<P>
At first the same places, Rome and Spain were in the forefront
of the new information age.  They explored, made new maps, and
had an active information rich culture. However with the coming
of the Reformation the Church lost its religious and information
monopoly and, in the inquisition, suppressed information and information
technology.  The Western Catholic Church made alliances with the
political powers and became like the Church of the Byzantine Empire.

<P>
The Protestant countries, Holland and England did not suppress
information technology. They became print intensive cultures in
the same way as we are a TV intensive culture.  A literate crafts
producing class developed- people who had grown up in crafts shops
and then learned to read.  They were able to use written records
to keep track of raw material and finished goods.  It set them
free of the old style of family based production. They invented
the basic structure of capitalism. The power equation and every
institution of life changed: 
<P>
&#183; Holland and then England became the most powerful nations
in Europe. 
<P>
&#183; Production went from crafts production to family owned
capitalist production.  
<P>
&#183; Social mobility increased and the notion that social place
was related to wealth rather than on birth was introduced. 
<P>
&#183; The family had been the major social and economically productive
unit. It included the biological family, apprentices, journeymen
and hired help to the strictly biological family. It became second
in importance to the economically productive unit.  
<P>
&#183; Literacy became the mark of adulthood thus defining the
non-literate as non-adults. 
<P>
&#183; Women ceased to be active in production and became identified
solely with home and family. 
<P>
&#183; Young children who had been seen as small adults emerged
as an age class 
<P>
&#183; The military became professionalized instead of being based
on personal fealty.
<P>
&#183; The political unit want from the city state to the nation
state. 
<H3>The Electric Revolution</H3>

<P>
The electric revolution continued the evolution of the individual
and shifted power from state sized units to the super power sized
units - the UK, the US and the USSR. It started with the telegraph.
The telegraph suggested a new organizational structure; the constrained
bureaucratic hierarchy. 
<P>
Hierarchies were not new but they had been based on class.  The
military hierarchy shows the traces of pre-telegraph hierarchy;
every non-commissioned person salutes every commissioned officer;
and in the notion that an officer is a gentleman.
<P>
A sense of individual importance based on professional competency
developed as a result of the new bureaucratic hierarchy.  The
individual at the bottom of the class ladder could give orders
to those at the top at the class ladder by virtue of his profession.
 For example, a conductor could tell the president of the railroad,
or the mayor of his town, to get on board. 
<P>
The new bureaucratic hierarchy constrained the power of managers.
 They could only give orders to those directly below them in the
managerial hierarchy. 
<P>
The introduction of the telephone extended the electric information
revolution and shifted the balance of economic power from London
to New York.
<P>
The electric information revolution, like the press, changed all
the institutions to favor groups with the greatest penetration
of information and information technology:  
<P>
&#183; In the United States a new national political consciousness
emerged in the north, where there was intense telegraph penetration
and organizations managed by the new hierarchies. The south stayed
in the older paradigm of family run plantations and small businesses,
states rights, and class based social structure. 
<P>
&#183; The family changed from the extended family group to the
nuclear family.  
<P>
&#183; As more and more of women's traditional work was done by
factories and machines they became more restricted. Women tried
to become re-integrated into the life of the nation through suffrage
movements and social activism. 
<P>
&#183; Child labor laws and public schools again changed and extended
the nature of childhood. 
<P>
And, as with the press there were conservative reactions: the
Civil War, Victorian morality, the Know-nothings, religious fundamentalism,
and xenophobia which resulted in immigration quotas.
<H3>The Digital Revolution</H3>

<P>
We are now in the midst of another information revolution.  Clearly
we see similar changes:
<P>
&#183; The power equation has shifted to favor the most information
intensive culture. 
<P>
&#183; The family is again being reduced from children and the
biological parents to the child and the care taking parent.
<P>
&#183; Childhood is disappearing as children experience sex and
violence vicariously on TV and in their day to day lives.
<P>
&#183; Gender roles and definitions are changing
<P>
&#183; And the individual has emerged from the faceless masses
as we see Baby Jessica or Scott O'Grady rescued, Rodney King beaten,
or follow the Bobbitt case with horror or amusement. 
<P>
<U><B>Other things are less clear</B>:</U>
<P>
&#183; Bureaucracy and organizational hierarchy has become problematic
words. Organizations need restructuring but don't quite know how

<P>
&#183; Crime statistics tell us our cities are safer than they
have ever been but we feel more threatened
<P>
&#183; We see the necessity of global regulation at the same time
we want to reduce national regulation and though we are the only
&quot;super-power&quot; we feel more helpless than ever
<P>
&#183; We know that there seems to be a need for a more global
world at the same time as it becomes less stable
<H3>Leaving the Default Position</H3>

<P>
First we must recognize that the change in paradigm is irreversible.
 We cannot go back to identity based on ethnicity or on a simple
definition of nationalism any more than we can return to the small
farm or the family business.  We must instead wage a two front
information technology war to bring the rest of the world into
the information age.
<P>
&#183; We must accept that our current paradigm is based on electric
not electronic thinking and redefine what National Security means
in the information age, based on our insights from previous information
revolutions, <I>and</I>
<P>
&#183; We must wage a campaign to foster the emergence of the
individual.
<P>
The first can be done by beginning conversations, holding conferences
like this one and others and by continuing the conversations internationally
&quot;on-line&quot;
<P>
The fostering of the individual can be done by making sure that
information providers are not fettered, controlled by, or dependent
on the existing political power structure.  
<P>
The peoples of Eastern Europe have never lived in information
free cultures. They went from the Byzantine empire to various
other forms of political control of information.  The social system
has been based on class whether that class is based on birth,
membership in the communist party, or membership in a certain
ethnic or religious group. 
<P>
Because they have never lived in an information free culture they
have never had the opportunity to develop individual identity
or a social system based on competency and professionalism. 
<P>
We can make war on these perceptual systems by giving and demanding
as a requirement for aid (military or economic) that we be allowed
to blanket the area with modern information technology tied to
the world wide information super-structure. Connecting people
to an independent source of information will foster economic and
political development.  It will develop individual identity. And,
it will be cheaper, less invasive, and more effective than any
of the dams,  power plants, wells, or agricultural projects of
the past.

</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
