<td valign=middle width=440>
<center><h2>
National Science Foundation  Blocks Internet to Iran!

</h2>
</center>
<B>
<P>Infowar.com was forwarded this posting yesterday by the Emergency News
Network.  (Thanks ENN)  It was not posted because we wanted to check it out
rather than churn the *rumor mill*.  Confirmation was received today.  </P>

For further info - check out:<BR>
<a href="http://www.netizen.com/netizen/96/35/special3a.html">www.netizen.com/netizen/96/35/special3a.html</a><BR>

<BR>
</B>

<BR>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>


Date: 27 Aug 1996 15:00:14 GMT<BR>
From: Donald Zhang Osborn osborndo@pilot.msu.edu</a><BR>
To: thrdwrld@sphinx.Gsu.EDU</a><BR>
Subject: Re: Blocking Internet to Iran<BR>
<BR>
<P>The following posting from soc.culture.iranian (dated 8/27/96) may
be of interest to readers of this group/list.  It actually consists
of two messages--a commentary from one individual preceding a
description of the apparent decision to cut internet access to Iran.
I pass it on without editorial comment, as I've just learned of it
and don't know the background or details...           DZO</P>

m.k.iranpour@fys.uio.no (Kambiz Iranpour) wrote:<BR>

<P>Today we were informed that the Internet US connection to Iran
through the Vienna University was disconnected by a strike of
a pen. This is a serious matter. We hear all the time about
how the Internet is creating more space for the individuals and
how at the end it increases the power of the individuals in
a society. We hear how the Internet is supposed to enhance
the democracy's voice in the countries that the information flow is
controlled. Until now we thought that the clergy is not
upgrading the bottleneck 9600 baud connection in Vienna in order
to control the information and we were sad about it. But
then what the Americans do ? They disconnect this small
flow !!! Are they in harmony with the most reactionary forces in Iran
which don't want any dialogue between the Iranian expatriates and
the Iranians inside Iran ? Do they want to close the window
to the outside on the Iranian people in order to create a cage
mentality there ? It seems so !! Otherwise why should
they do such a thing exactly when they are increasing the VOA
sendings over Iran through Kuwait ? It means that they
don't want the dialogue between Iranians inside and outside
Iran to continue but they want to have a control over
the propaganda line !! This is not only a sad story about
controlling information but also attacking the rights of the
Iranian community in US !! Tomorrow they may cut the telephone
lines !! These actions limit the communication
between Iranians inside and outside Iran and takes away
the option to have a dialogue open with the people of Iran
by the Iranian expatriate community. Not long ago Time magazine
had an article on the Internet in Iran and how it is
transforming the face of the country and revolutionizing
the human intercommunication. It said give the Internet 5
years and it'll revolutionize the country (in a positive
sense.) It is the power of the Information Technology which
gives the individual more leverage. This right today
has been restricted by a vicious or a thoughtless action, at
the same time that the right of the Iranian community to
write and receive mail from their families in not a distant
future has been taken away from them. I ask the Iranian
community in the US to show unity and protest against
these kinds of capricious policies which limit the prospect of
democracy, ristrict the rights of the individuals and take away your
rights. Whether as an individual or as an organization you should
let your dismay to be heard. Tomorrow more of your rights can be
in danger !!!</P>
<BR>
Payman Arabshahi wrote :<BR>

From: Wilfried Woeber woeber@cc.univie.ac.at<BR>
Computer Center - ACOnet, Vienna University<BR>

<P>Ladies and Gentlemen !</P>

<P>Due to U.S. Government decisions (embargo), we were ordered recently by the
U.S. National Science Foundation (Steve Goldstein) to cease providing
connectivity for Iran on our infrastructure to, and transitting the NSF
supported infastructure in, the USA.</P>

<P>So, to summarize, it is no longer possible to access networks in Iran,
which are connected to and by Ebone, (from most of?) the US part of the
Internet.</P>

<P>As an aside, we do no longer expect an upgrade for the connection from
Tehran to our site, although it wouldn't make a difference for you anyway.</P>

<P>While we regret that situation, we are not in a position to act contrary to
this request.</P>

Best regards, and sorry!<BR>
Wilfried.<BR>
<BR>
 --------------------------------------------------------------------------<BR>
  Wilfried Woeber                :  e-mail: Woeber@CC.UniVie.ac.at<BR>
  Computer Center - ACOnet       :<BR>
  Vienna University              :  Tel: +43 1 4065822 355<BR>
  Universitaetsstrasse 7         :  Fax: +43 1 4065822 170<BR>
  A-1010 Vienna, Austria, Europe :  NIC: WW144<BR>
 --------------------------------------------------------------------------<BR>
                               *       *       *

Who is responsible for this?<BR>
<BR>
Dr. Steven N. Goldstein<BR>
Program Director, Interagency and International Coordination<BR>
Division of Networking and Communications Research and Infrastructure<BR>
Directorate for Computer and Information Science and Engineering<BR>
National Science Foundation<BR>
4201 Wilson Boulevard, Room 1175<BR>
Arlington, Virginia 22230<BR>
Tel: +1 703 306 1949<BR>
Fax: +1 703 306 0621<BR>
Email: goldstein@nsf.gov<BR>


--
Payman Arabshahi                        Tel  : (205) 895-6380<BR>
Dept. of Electrical & Computer Eng.     Fax  : (205) 895-6803<BR>
University of Alabama in Huntsville     
payman@ebs330.eb.uah.edu<BR>
Huntsville, AL 35899<BR>
http://www.eb.uah.edu/ece<BR>
 
<BR>


</td>

