<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<img border=0 width=43 height=43 src="../../images/class1.gif">
</td>
<td valign=middle width=440>
<center><h2>

It'll Never Happen To You
</h2>
by Winn Schwartau

</Center>
<BR>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>

<p>You never think it's going to happen to you.  Well, my friends, it does.</p>
<p>Over the last few years I have written about a number of security relevant events which I have run into on a personal basis:</p>
<UL>
<LI>Captured "Most Wanted" cyber-felon Kevin Mitnick adapted my electronic identity to do his thing on an antique WELL account of mine. <BR>
<LI>My warhero cousin, Bill Wells, was victimized for tens of thousands of dollars by high tech thieves who adapted his identity, got credit, credit cards, bought cars and so on . . . all in his name.  The pressure finally killed him.<BR>
<LI> My wife is inundated with letters from bottom sucking lawyers in search of mauled clients after she is in a traffic accident: the next day!<BR>
<LI>My bank tellers yell out secret access codes across the lobby.<BR>
<LI>My supermarket clerks write down and openly share passcodes to the store's computers.<BR>
<LI> A local cop accesses the NCIC computers from his patrol car and then proceeds to show me how to do it step by step  . . . including his passwords.  (I pretended to be a know-nothing guy with an interest in computers.)<BR>
</UL>
<p>But in the last several weeks, the rules changed and I have been the targeted victim of, ah, how shall I call them, criminal hackers (to use Mich Kabay's clear distinction).</p>
<p>As most readers of my books and work know, I am not inherently against hacking: in fact I tend to agree with Robert Steele of OSS that hackers are a valuable commodity to the US, especially in a defensive mode. I believe that we need their skills and knowledge to work our way safely into Cyberspace, and if the recent Mitnick busts are any example, the FBI agrees at least somewhat. </p>
<p>So it came as quite a surprise to me when the first warning came.</p>
<p>"They're out to get you," I was told by an underground source. I was in-between planes and was checking in to see what was new.</p>
<p>"Who is and why?"</p>
<p>I won't give out the names in public (libel and all that) but I have passed them on to the FBI.  "They don't like you for what you write about them."</p>
<p>Huh?  I've never really trashed 'dissed' on hackers: I tell 'em just keep it all legal - that has been my credo.  So why come after me?  There was no real answer so I sort of forgot about it.  </p>
<p>That Friday night it started.  A couple of harassing calls.  A call from a group of hackers who passed on private information about Time writer Josh Quittner who himself had been the victim of hackers because of his book.  So, was the warning accurate? </p>
<p>Then I received a sheath of documents which included GTE security information, "find the hacker" source code from programs GTE supposedly uses to track them down, access codes, network diagrams and print outs from the service address utility listing me and my neighbors phones and other pertinent information.</p>
<p>And a couple more harassing calls.</p>
<p>Then, my toll records were pulled.  Many people with whom I speak want their names and numbers kept secret for their own reasons, and they have phones connected every which way to avoid detection or eavesdropping.</p>
<p>I received an angry call from one such person.  "You're on my s___ list."  Huh?  "Who'd you give my number to?"  No one,  no one.  "Well, these guys found me and they said they have your toll records."  </p>
<p>Toll records are a list of the long distance calls you make - like the monthly bill that lists where you have called.  If someone gets a hold of that list, they then have access to the numbers that are supposedly private.  In this case, the privacy was gone and I had some upset friends.</p>
<p>I first contacted GTE.  Or tried to.  I explained what was happening and asked for the security folks.  The operators were reluctant to give me any numbers and tried to get me to tell them what was happening.  No, no.  Please, just give me the number for security.  Battle, battle, and I finally got it.</p>
<p>I explained what I though was happening, and said that I had records from their system which means someone had indeed broken in.  "No, can't be.  We're secure."  Right. Besides, we don't have any toll records here. Call your carrier.</p>
<p>I use a billing service, for my long distance carrier, (no names please) and called them.  "You have to talk to us.  We won't let you talk directly with your provider."  Right.  A couple of phone calls later and I reached the carrier and told them what was happening. "Can't be us. We're secure."</p>
<p>This was getting old fast.</p>
<p>Now, think of this for a minute.  I supposedly know what I'm doing  :-)  and I know who to call, and how to explain it and so on, yet look at the runaround.  What happens to Ozzie and Harriet from Peoria when they call about security problems and don't understand it or can't explain it?  Think what they must go through!</p>
<p>Since I could prove nothing other than the GTE documents I had in hand, I had a choice of pushing the carrier hard or letting it drop.  </p>
<p>Finally I got a hold of some people at my LD carrier who knew what they were doing and we put a couple of systems in place to avoid future social engineering and hacks against the switch.  But GTE?  Nada. Nothing. </p>
<p>If you run into trouble like this, you can try your local phone company, but I wholeheartedly suggest that you contact your local FBI office and make a report.  They are getting better and better at this and will take action.  Good luck.</p>





</td>

<td width=80>

</td>
</tr>
</table>
<br>
