<tr>
<td width=440>


<H2><Center>
US Soldier Accused of "Cracking" for foreign power.
</H2>
</Center>
<P>FORT BRAGG, N.C., Aug. 21 (UPI) -- The army has charged a Fort Bragg
soldier with breaking into a military computer system and giving secret
materials to another country, a published report said Wednesday.</P>
   <P>According to military documents, Pfc. Eric O. Jenott, 20, distributed
"secret computer passwords relating to the national defense," an offense
which amounts to spying, the Fayetteville, N.C., Observer-Times said.</P>
   <P>Jenott's attorney said his client is not a spy and did not intend to
hurt the United States.</P>
   <P>"He is not a criminal, just a computer hacker who happened to access
a very important and expensive, supposedly impenetrable system," Timothy
Dunn said.</P>
   <P>The army considers many details of the case classified, Dunn said.
The report did not name which country may have been involved.</P>
   <P>Jenott, of Seattle, was charged with espionage, damaging military
property, larceny and breaking into government computer systems, the
newspaper said.</P>
   <P>He has been jailed since June 26 at Camp Lejeune Marine Base and
could be sentenced to life in a military prison if convicted at a court-
martial.</P>
   <P>Fort Bragg officials said the case was under investigation and
declined to comment.</P>
  <P> In Graham, Wash., Jenott's father, John, said his son discovered an
apparent security weakness in a military communications system several
months ago, but he claimed superiors paid little attention.</P>
  <P> Later, one of his superiors appeared to be pleased Jenott discovered
the problem, his father said.</P>
   <P>Jenott was surprised when he was arrested and accused of compromising
the communications system by accessing it, according to his father.</P>
   <P>"He said, 'I'd rather face the death penalty than confess to
something I didn't do,'" Jenott's father said.</P>
   <P>Prosecutors have decided not to pursue the death penalty, the
newspaper said.</P>
  <P> Jenott is a communication switch operator in Company B, 50th Signal
Battalion, 35th Signal Brigade.</P>
  <P> A military court is scheduled decide next month whether Jenott must
continue living behind bars.</P>


<BR>

</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
