<H3><Center>
UK: SKY'S NO LIMIT FOR HACKERS.<BR>
By RICHARD GRANT.<BR>
</H3>
</Center>
<BR>
December 31, 1996<BR>
<P>COMPUTER hackers claim to have cracked satellite TV broadcaster BSkyB's security
codes so they can receive its channels on the cheap.
Software released on the Internet last week allows viewers with a satellite dish
and a set-top decoder to pirate Sky's premium L27-a-month sports and movie
service, using a smartcard for its basic L12 service.
<P>The pirate software is advertised as a `program to activate all Sky channels'.
It works on any home PC linked to a L60 mail-order black box that re-programs
the Sky smartcard.
<P>Sky has often been forced to upgrade its smartcards and electronic
counter-measures to defeat hackers and card copiers.
The latest smartcard, first made available in October 1995, has been the most
successful and long-lasting until this week.
<P>It was thought to be hacker-proof until it was reprogrammed to intercept Sky
pay-per-view events for free, including the Bruno v Tyson fight at L9.99.
Sky says its policy is to `take all technical and legal steps' to protect its
services. [Microsoft boss Bill Gates is reported to have become the latest
victim of the Unamailer, a US Internet terrorist, who jammed his personal e-mail
letter box with thousands of messages putting it out of action on Christmas Eve.

<P>UNITED KINGDOM <BR>
MAIL ON SUNDAY 29/12/96 </P>

</td>
</tr>
</table>


