<td width=440>


<H3><Center>
Major Internet Server Platform Vulnerable to Hacker Attacks<BR>
</H3>
</Center>
<BR>
<P> Microsofts Flagship Product Windows NT Server is Vulnerable to Serious 
 Hacker Attacks Because of Security Flaws
 
<P> San Francisco, December 17, 1996:   Microsoft NT, one of the internets 
 most dominant platforms has been discovered to be extremely vulnerable to
 hacker and security attacks.  Taking their cue from publicly released 
 Microsoft documents, the internets most famous hackers are writing and 
 releasing code to exploit the weaknesses of Microsofts flagship product, 
 Windows NT Server.  "We fully intend to release the code and programs 
 that exploits NTs weaknesses" said a noted hacker anonymously named 
 "Bob". The security problems were exposed in a December 16th Information 
 Week article written by Stuart Johnston 
 (<A HREF="HTTP://techweb.cmp.com/iw/610/10iunt.htm">http://techweb.cmp.com/iw/610/10iunt.htm</A>) and while no specifics were 
 made public, many hackers who have read the article were incensed at the 
 indifferent response given by a Microsoft spokesman.
 
<P> Dark Tangent, president of Defcon and organizer of an annual hacker 
 gathering said, "Its unfortunate that Microsoft is ignoring the problem 
 and has some marketing guy making lackadaisical pronouncements on a very 
 serious issue that can potentially undermine thousands of internet sites 
 and corporations." 
 
<P><B> Microsofts Folly</B>
 
<P> The details of NTs weakness were outlined in a little known publicly 
 released Microsoft document entitled, Common Internet File System 
 Protocol (CIFS/1.0).  Hacker "Bob" said, "We simply took the details of 
 the document and built programs to exploit the weaknesses."  The weakness
 leaves Microsofts NT Servers vulnerable to man-in-the-middle and 
 authentication attacks that could allow malicious hackers, disgruntled 
 employees or industrial spies to steal data, get and forge legitimate 
 users identities and passwords or simply render entire web sites or 
 systems inoperable.  Asked where and when the programs will be released, 
 hacker "Bob" said, "We hope to publish the attacks in either 2600 
 magazine or the freely available hacker zine called as phrack."
 
<P> Various internet underground sources claim that various versions of the 
 attack are freely circulating in the hacker community and is now the 
 subject of both design and debate in various internet news groups and 
 forums.  Another noted hacker named "nachos" from the hacker group 
 dis.org said, "There is already working code to snarf user names and 
 passwords. There is now design work undergoing to package these in trojan
 horses and other delivery mechanisms.  This should serve as a wake-up 
 call to corporate America.  Take heed or be kneed".

<P><B>Moderator's comment:</B>


<P>Bravo, bravo, bravo! It's about time someone pointed out the obvious about
Windows NT. This operating system has been sweeping the workstation world.

<P>According to an International Data Corporation (IDC) report, "Windows NT on
Intel platforms is the biggest impending threat to traditional workstation
vendors."(1)
 
<P>What has motivated this invasion? A recent Dataquest survey reports that
users of Windows NT running on a RISC platform are the most satisfied of all
users of advanced desktop and workstation systems. This study concludes,
"High-end Intel-based PCs and RISC PCs running Windows NT have clearly made
inroads into the traditional markets of Unix workstations."(2)

<P>In fact, Windows NT is making more than "inroads." It might be more accurate
to characterize this as the Windows NT "invasion." Check out the numbers.

<P>If today's invasion is unchecked, an IDC report projects that the Unix-based
Web server market share will fall from the 65% of 1995 to only 25% by the
year 2000. The Windows NT share is projected to grow to 32%.  This weak
future for Unix Web servers is reinforced by an IDC report reporting that
market share of all Unix systems is now falling at a compound annual rate of
decline of -17% for the foreseeable future, while Windows NT is growing in
market share by 20% per year. Reasons given for this are the support,
training and marketing backing of NT.(3)

<P>Of course a big problem with Windows NT steamrollering Unix is the security
issue. Because Windows NT source code has not been publicly released, it has
been difficult to evaluate its security problems. By contrast, Unix flaws
are widely discussed -- and exploited. So this has led to a perception that
Windows NT is actually a more secure system than Unix-type operating systems.

<P>But perhaps with the impending release of details on Windows NT security
flaws, the Windows NT invasion may be held at bay. Long live Unix!

<P>(1)Laura C. Segervall, "Worldwide Workstation Forecast, 1995-2000," IDC
#11270, March 1996, 1.<BR>
(2)"Advanced Desktop and Workstation Computing Worldwide," Dataquest
WKST-WW-UW-9601, Sept. 9, 1996, 52, 53.<BR>
(3)Mark Winther, "The Global Market for Public and Private Internet Server
Software," IDC #11202, April 1996, 10, 11.</P>

