<tr>
<td width=440>


<H3><Center>
England's Labour Party's Web Page "hacked"<BR>
</H3>
</Center>
<BR>
<BR>


<P>ENN Daily Report

<P>Tuesday - 12/17/96 -Vol. 2, No. 352
<P><CENTER>                     *****Computer/InfoWar*****</CENTER>



<P>By Jim Fay, Assoc. Editor

<P>The Web Page belonging to the British Labour Party was reportedly hit by
a hacker on two different occasions recently. The unknown hacker(s),
which was only identified as a male with a US accent, hit the Web Page a
week ago, and changed the title of the Page, and tampered with the links
to other pages, directing them to Web Pages containing pornography. The
Page was restored within twenty minutes of the finding the damage.

<P>However, the hacker hit the Page again last week, this time  criticizing
Labour Party politicians. The Labour Party has asked the Police to step
in and investigate the continued invasion of the Web Page. Newsbytes
Magazine is also reporting that a third attempt was  made on the Page.
The Labour Party's Web Page can be accessed at: http://www.labour.co.uk

<P><CENTER>              *****Terrorism/Secondary Attacks*****</CENTER>

<P>SGT. Assaf Banor Dies After Two Years in Coma

<P>By Yechiel Spira, SNS News Service and C.L. Staten, ERRI

<P>(SNS News Service - Shomron-Israel) Sgt. Assaf Banor, IDF, age 20, died
today of wounds sustained in the January 22, 1995 Bet Lid suicide
terrorist attack. Assaf was very critically injured in the second blast
at Bet Lid as he ran towards the injured victims of the first blast to
render first aid. He regained consciousness for eight days in Hadassah
Ein Keren Hospital and then slipped back into a coma and was transferred
to Bet Levenstein Rehabilitation Hospital.

<P>For almost two year he lingered in a coma until this morning when he
finally succumbed to his wounds. Assaf would have been 21 next month.
Assaf brings the death toll from the Bet Lid attack to twenty-two.
(Source: SNS News Service and Channel 12 TV News..12/16..8:00pm)

<P>(ENN) ERRI analysts said that the tragic death of SGT. Banor, does point
out, however, a potentially glaring error in training that was exploited
by an extremist bomber. In this case, Banor rushed into an unsecured
scene of an unexplained explosion and was killed by a secondary device,
triggered just for the purpose of killing rescue and security personnel.


<P>The Bet Lid situation was not the first, nor the last occurence of
command or delay-detonated devices being used to attack medical and
rescue personnel. A similar circumstance just occurred in N. Ireland,
where a medical facility was targeted with a second bomb, to be set-off
as victims and medics arrived. It has apparently become a common tactic
among some of the more radical terrorist groups.

<P>It should point out the tactical necessity of sweeping and clearing of
an explosion scene and immediately securing an inner and outer
perimeter. In the Bet Lid bombing, a second assailant remained on the
scene and eventually ran into a crowd of emergency responders and IDF
personnel, then detonating his device, killing SGT. Banor and 21 others.
Had the scene been cleared and secured, he would not have been able to
carry out his deadly mission.

<P>In future terrorist incidents, it is highly recommended by ERRI that
medical and emergency response personnel be constantly aware of the
possibility of a secondary explosive device and that law enforcement and
military personnel set about establishing multiple secure perimeters and
beginning a bomb search at the earliest possible tactical opportunity.
To do otherwise can prove fatal, as evidenced by this Israeli incident.

<P><CENTER>                  *****IEDs/Stateless Warfare*****</CENTER>

<P>San Diego Arson Officials Warn of "Bottle Bombs"

<P>By C.L. Staten, Senior Analyst

<P>(ENN) Bomb technicians from the San Diego, CA Metro Arson Task force are
reporting an increase in the number of people buildng and exploding
so-called "bottle bombs." In a 12/14/96 report in the San Diego Tribune,
bomb experts say that have seen several improvised explosive devices in
recent days, all of them built from 2-liter plastic soda bottles, using
a variety of chemicals.

<P>Paul Copher, ENN Counter-Terrorist Analyst-at-Large, and former IED
instructor for the federal government, told ENN that these devices can
be dangerous and often cause injuries to unsuspecting persons as they
are struck by flying shards of plastic. Worse, says Copher, the shrapnel
may not be detectable in X-rays and could result in potentially deadly
infections. Victims may also be splashed by caustic chemicals when the
devices detonate, according to Copher. The contents of these
"bottle-bombs" could cause blindness or even death, if the victim is
close enough to them as they go off.</P>

</td>
</tr>
</table>


</td>

<td width=80>
<br>

