<!-- Article Body Table ---------------------------------------------->

<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<img border=0 width=43 height=43 src="../../images/pent.gif">
</td>
<td valign=middle width=440>

</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>

<h3><Center>TROOPS IN BOSNIA LEFT OUT OF INFORMATION LOOP, ANALYSIS
FINDS<BR>

By Bryan Bender</H3>

<BR>
</Center>

</table>
<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<td width=440>

December 17, 1996<BR><BR>

<P>
Perhaps those of us who believe we are on the threshold of a 
Revolution In Military Affairs made possible by recent leaps
ahead in information technology need to consider the following
excerpt from today's  Defense Daily:


<P>U.S. soldiers keeping the peace in Bosnia have benefitted little from advances
in information technology, despite Pentagon efforts to equip them with the
latest capabilities, according to a recent analysis of the operation. 

<P>The wide array of advanced communications and intelligence systems used in
Bosnia has benefitted the higher-ups in the chain-of-command, while
subordinate units--who do the dirty work of carrying out the 1995 Dayton Peace
Accords--have operated much as they did 20 years ago,
according to Information Operations in Bosnia--A Preliminary Assessment. 

<P>"Elaborate information flows between higher command levels do not always
translate into better support for the warfighter," the assessment states. "In
fact, life in Bosnia has not changed very much for the American soldier
because the information revolution largely stops at division level." 

<P>The assessment was authored by Army Col. Kenneth Allard, who recently retired
as the senior military fellow at the Institute for National Strategic Studies.
It was published in the November issue of the Institute's Strategic Forum and
reflects Allard's own insights after spending time with the 1st Armored
Division in Bosnia. 

<P>The findings contradict numerous statements by Pentagon officials and press
reports that contend the NATO peacekeeping operation has introduced the
military to the information age for the first time. 

<P>Information Too Little and Too Late

<P>As an example of how tactical battlefield information and intelligence rarely
gets to the soldiers who need it, Allard tells the story of a brigade
commander who recently requested satellite pictures of his area of
responsibility but didn't receive them for three weeks. And when they finally
arrived, the imagery was six months old. 

<P>"Despite the imperative of supporting the warfighter, the river of information
available to U.S. military forces in Bosnia often diminishes to a trickle by
the time it reaches the soldiers actually executing peacekeeping missions,"
the report says. 

<P>Allard says the reasons for this include communications pipelines too "narrow"
to efficiently carry digital data to the field, widespread use of "outmoded"
tactical equipment, and automated systems "easily overwhelmed" by what data is
available. 

<P>"But these are some of the more pernicious effects of an unwritten but
well-understood rule: the higher the headquarters, the more elaborate the
information trappings--and vice-versa," the report  says. 

<P>Allard found other reasons for the less-than-optimal information flow in
Bosnia. 

<P>Military forces have historically been hampered by adverse weather conditions
and other natural enemies, Allard points out.  But in Bosnia, it is worse
because automation systems have been arranged "ad hoc" in command centers and
field outposts that are spread out along lengthy supply lines. 

<P>"Such ad hoc arrangements make it more difficult to maintain computers and
electronic equipment or to defend them," according to the report. Allard
describes the Army's automation network as a "system of kluges," rather than a
"system of systems." 

<P>One result of the ad hoc structure is a fast-growing number of computer
viruses. "Conventional wisdom among U.S. units is that 50 percent of their
personal computers have suffered from viruses of one kind or another," the
assessment states. 

<P>Lastly, Allard believes more attention must be given to doctrine and training
when considering information operations. "Advances in information technology
are of military value only to the extent
that they are accompanied by coherent doctrine, organizations, equipment, and
people--to say nothing of the time needed to make them function as a team," he
writes. 

<P>Copyright 1996 Defense Daily </P>

</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
