<HEAD><TITLE>
DOS and SYN Flooding

</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffFF">


<!-- Header/Nav-Bar Table -------------------------------------------->

<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td valign=top width=48>
<a href="infosec.html-ssi"><img width=48 height=68 border=0 src="../../images/back.gif" alt="Back"></a>
</td>
<td valign=top width=48>
<a href="http://www.infowar.com/index.html-ssi"><img width=48 height=68 border=0 src="../../images/home.gif" alt="Home"></a>
</td>
<td valign=top width=48>
<a href="http://www.infowar.com/search_reg.html-ssi"><img width=48 height=68 border=0 src="../../images/srch.gif" alt="Search"></a>
</td>
<td valign=top align=right width=236>
<img border=0 width=236 height=68 src="../../images/line.gif">
</td>

<td width=200>
<img vspace=3 border=0 src="../../images/dot_spac.gif"><br>
<A HREF="http://www.infowar.com/sponsors/sponsors.html-ssi
"><img width=200 height=68 border=0 src="http://www.infowar.com/sponsors/ad4.gif"></A>
</td>
</tr>
</tr>
</table>
<br>
<IMG ALT="[Bomb2]" SRC="../../images/bomb2_li.gif" width=580><p>


<!-- Article Body Table ---------------------------------------------->

<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<img border=0 width=43 height=43 src="../../images/lock.gif">
</td>
<td valign=middle width=440>
<center><h3>

DOS and SYN Flooding<BR>
By Elizabeth Weise
</h3>


</Center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>
December 17 1996<BR>
<BR>

<P>AP Cyberspace Writer

<P>   The computer assault that cut WebCom's customers off from the World Wide Web
is a kind of "denial of service" attack called a "SYN-flood." 
<P>   SYN-flooding involves sending a continuous stream of forged messages to a
targeted computer, keeping it constantly busy and locking out legitimate users. 
<P>   It exploits the so-called "synchronization feature" of the transmission
control protocol, the agreed-upon set of rules by which the Internet runs. 
<P>   When users connects to a Web site, they are actually asking the computer on
which that Web site is stored to send files containing the requested Web page. 
<P>   That give and take begins with a three-stage interaction between the computer
looking for data and the computer sending data. 
<P>   When the first computer begins to talk to the second, it sends a message that
means "Hello." The second computer answers with the equivalent of, "Hello, how
are you?" 
<P>   Now that both computers have established they're listening and synchronized,
they exchange confirmation of the connection and only then do they begin to
transmit Web pages. 
<P>   In a SYN-flood attack, hackers send a series of forged messages to the
target. Because the messages are forged, they don't have a real return address
for the computer to send its "Hello, how are you?" response to. 
<P>   Because of the way the transmission control protocol is written, the computer
under attack waits -- as long as a minute -- for the second computer to respond.

<P>   Because the first computer is being flooded with these forged and
unanswerable messages -- as many as 200 a second -- its storage buffers fill up
as it struggles to complete the connection. It quickly ceases to answer new
requests for connections by legitimate users while it attempts to deal with the
congestion problem -- meaning anyone trying to access a WebCom site wouldn't get
through.

<P>1996 Associated Press</P>


<BR>

</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<br>
