<center><h3>
<P>Web site helps track fugitives<BR>
  <BR>

</h3>


</Center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>

December 17, 1996<BR>
 
<P>UPn  13/12/96 16:52   


<P>Copyright 1996 United Press International. All rights reserved.
<P>The following news report may not be republished or redistributed, in whole or
in part, without the prior written consent of United Press International.
  
<P>   WASHINGTON, Dec. 13 (UPI) -- The long arm of U.S. law enforcement is now
reaching into cyberspace.
<P>   The Justice Department and Voice of America already have set up an
international fugitive alert service.
<P>   And now the service includes a World Wide Web site that has been switched on
for computer users and law enforcement around the world.
<P>   The department and Voice of America launched a weekly broadcast,
International Crime Alert, in August. The VOA broadcasts around the world in
about 50 languages.
<P>   Once a fugitive is featured on the broadcast, his or her photograph and
identifying information is posted on the home page of the United States
Information Agency (www.usia.gov).
<P>   In the Justice Department, the "fugitive unit" in the Office of International
Affairs will be coordinating extradition for high-profile U.S. and foreign
fugitives.
<P>   The unit is designed to work closely with a broad spectrum of law enforcement
agencies, including the FBI and the Drug Enforcement Agency, and the State
Department and INTERPOL.
<P>   The fugitive unit also has its own home page (<A HREF="HTTP://www.usdoj.
gov/criminal/oiafug/fugitives.htm">http://www.usdoj.
gov/criminal/oiafug/fugitives.htm</A>).
<P> ---<BR>
   Copyright 1996 by United Press International.
   All rights reserved.<BR>
 ---</P>

