<IMG ALT="[Bomb2]" SRC="../../images/bomb2_li.gif" width=580><p>


<!-- Article Body Table ---------------------------------------------->

<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<img border=0 width=43 height=43 src="jobs3.gif">
</td>
<td valign=middle width=440>
<center><h3>



<B>
 Information and Communications Policy Position<BR>
</B>
</h3>
<BR>
</Center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>
<BR>
12 December 1996<BR>
<BR>
<P>The Georgia Tech School of Public Policy seeks applications and nominations
for a tenure track faculty position in public policy, focusing on
information and communications policy. Rank is open.

<P>A secondary specialty in one or more of the following areas is helpful, but
not required: public law, intellectual property, computer science,
information management, public finance, quantitative methods.

<P>Ph.D. or equivalent at the beginning of employment is required. Women and
minorities are particularly encouraged to apply. Ideally, the successful
candidate will commence employment in Fall 1997.

<P>The successful candidate will add to existing teaching and research
strengths in the School's  information and communications policy group. The
new faculty member will be encouraged to collaborate with faculty on
research and courses in the College of Computing, the Dupree School of
Management, the Program on the Consequences of the Information Revolution,
and the Georgia Center for Advanced Telecommunications Technology. A
priority in Georgia Tech's current capital campaign is to establish an
interdisciplinary center for research on issues related to information
technology, policy, and management.

<P>Established in 1990, the School of Public Policy at Georgia Tech is an
academic unit of the Ivan Allen College of Management, Policy, and
International Affairs. The School's specialization's, besides information
and communications policy, are in the fields of science and technology
policy, environmental policy, urban and economic development policy.  The
School is committed to interdisciplinary public policy studies and its
current faculty includes faculty with specializations in (among others)
economics, political science, engineering, philosophy, decision sciences,
and law. The School currently offers a Master of Science in Public Policy,
which enrolls more than sixty students, and a Ph.D. program. A BS. degree
in public policy has recently been approved. The successful candidate is
expected to teach at the graduate and undergraduate levels.

<P>Located in mid-town Atlanta, Georgia Tech has an attractive campus and a
diverse student body of 13,000. The University is an Affirmative
Action/Equal Opportunity employer.
Consideration of applicants begins immediately and will continue until the
position is filled. Letters of application or nomination should be sent to:</P>
<PRE>
                Mr. Chris Everson
                School of Public Policy
                Georgia Tech
                Atlanta, GA 30332-0345
</PRE>
<P>Applicants should include a curriculum  vita and the names, addresses, and
phone numbers of three persons who may be contacted for references.

<P>Posted 12/12/96</P>

<HR>
 Dr. Myron L. Cramer <<A HREF="MAILTOmyron.cramer@gtri.gatech.edu:">myron.cramer@gtri.gatech.edu</A>><BR>
