<!-- Article Body Table ---------------------------------------------->

<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<img border=0 width=43 height=43 src="../../images/lock.gif">
</td>
<td valign=middle width=440>
<center><h3>

Export Encryption Compromise- It Doesn't Look Good<BR>
by Betty G. OHearn<BR>
Infowar.Com<BR>
</h3>


</Center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>
December 09 1996<BR>
<BR>
<P>You recall that at the beginning of October, Vice President Gore made an announcement  that the Administration offered a compromise that would permit computer companies  to export data scrambling (encryption) software  with a hitch; the companies had to agree to establish systems that would enable keys to the codes, be given to law enforcement officials with a court warrant. 

<P>The compromise is in a precarious state as the numbers of American companies are rejecting it. One of the companies, IBM who had a major part in brokering the compromise, is having second thoughts because the Administration has not kept up with their part of the bargain relevant to the compromise.  IBM officials aren't talking but other computer software companies are beginning to get vocal.

<P>Roel Pieper, chief executive  and vice chairman of Tandem Computers based in Cupertino, California told the NY Times, "We really feel that there has been a bait and switch situation and I'm not going to be silent about it.  The Government is mortgaging the future of the computer industry."  Tandem products are widely used in the banking industry and other markets.

<P>Sun Microsystems, another major player in the encryption software business who previous supported the compromise with major reservations, is now opposing it.  

<P>The compromise included a plan for transferring oversight of data-scrambling export from the State Department to the Commerce Dept.  Computer companies see the Commerce Dept. as more supportive of American business and industry.

<P>A number of computer companies had viewed the compromise with the Administration as better than years of impasse between the industry and Government on the issue of exporting encryption software.  On November 15, an executive order was signed.  Within that document, the government officials will be given the upper hand in delivering the key-recovery system.  The order prescribes a system that may permit law enforcement officials to unscramble messages while transmission is active rather than after as the previous compromise stated. The order also has another downside.  It indicated that requests for export while being reviewed, would not take into account whether technology comparables were already in place overseas.  It had been expected by the industry that foreign availability would be a prime consideration.  Such is the case when the Dept. of Commerce reviews exports of high technology products.

<P>Vice President Gore was sent a letter by the Business Software Alliance.  The BSA based out of DC, represents major software publishers. The letter stated that the Alliance felt the Administration was going in the wrong direction on the issue of data encryption. Second VP of BSA, Robert W. Holleyman 2nd, told the NY Times, "It appears that significant backtracking has occurred since the October 1 announcement, and therefore, we seriously doubt that the regulations will work, meet consumer commands, or be accepted by the private sector unless the Administration changes its approach immediately."

<P>It has been reported, unofficially, that a group of computer manufacturers met earlier this past week at the White House.  One person described the session as rather "difficult."  The group met to discuss the executive order and the draft regulations that will be issued by the Government by the end of the year.  

<P>At the present time, these data scrambling technologies are becoming critical as foreign and US companies rush to develop  electronic commerce systems that will be utilized over the Internet. Computer and telephone communications without fear of eavesdropping are a hot item.

<P>The development director of Internet security for Hewlett-Packard, Doug McGowan, stated "We do understand that the Government has legitimate concerns, but what we care about is that we can compete on a global scale with our products.  We will yell loud and clear if it gets to a point where we can't."

<P>Where is all this going?  Hard to say now....but it does not look good. Where we go from here on this issue will have a bearing on American technologies.  Let's hope the Administration reviews this carefully and overturns the executive order.  A compromise was reached.  Let's go with the compromise!!  Or,  what we will have all over again?  C L I P P E R....</P>


<a href="betty@infowar.com">betty@infowar.com</a><BR>
Copyright 1996 by Infowar.com<BR>
<BR>
Compiled from several articles<BR>
Quotes from NY Times<BR>


<BR>

</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
