<HEAD><TITLE>

US ARMY PKI

</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffFF">


<!-- Header/Nav-Bar Table -------------------------------------------->

<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td valign=top width=48>
<a href="mil_c4i.html-ssi"><img width=48 height=68 border=0 src="../../images/back.gif" alt="Back"></a>
</td>
<td valign=top width=48>
<a href="http://www.infowar.com/index.html-ssi"><img width=48 height=68 border=0 src="../../images/home.gif" alt="Home"></a>
</td>
<td valign=top width=48>
<a href="http://www.infowar.com/search_reg.html-ssi"><img width=48 height=68 border=0 src="../../images/srch.gif" alt="Search"></a>
</td>
<td valign=top align=right width=236>
<img border=0 width=236 height=68 src="../../images/line.gif">
</td>

<td width=200>
<img vspace=3 border=0 src="../../images/dot_spac.gif"><br>
<A HREF="http://www.infowar.com/sponsors/sponsors.html-ssi
"><img width=200 height=68 border=0 src="http://www.infowar.com/sponsors/ad5.gif"></A>
</td>
</tr>
</tr>
</table>
<br>
<IMG ALT="[Bomb2]" SRC="../../images/bomb2_li.gif" width=580><p>


<!-- Article Body Table ---------------------------------------------->

<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<img border=0 width=43 height=43 src="../../images/pent.gif">
</td>
<td valign=middle width=440>

</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>

<h3><Center>US ARMY PKI</H3>

<BR>
</Center>

</table>
<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<td width=440>

December 07, 1996<BR><BR>

<P>     The US Army Peacekeeping Institute (PKI) participated in this 
     conference, the following report is submitted.
     
     
<P>     "Peacekeeping in Europe and Europeans in Peacekeeping" sponsored by 
     the UN Training School, Ireland, 19 November 1996.   
     
<P>        a.  Session I, "Peacekeeping Since the Cold War,"  Professor 
     Halliday.  He made the following points to outline the changes in 
     peacekeeping since the Cold War:
     
<P>                -  Peacekeeping operations (PKOs) have proliferated.  The 
     focus has  shifted from third world to Europe with OSCE alone involved 
     in 10 operations.          In addition, there has been a change in 
     character--more robust ROE and greater     involvement of the great 
     powers.
     
<P>                -  Kuwait gave a strong impetus to PKOs--especially the 
     intervention in    northern Iraq to help the Kurds and the precedent 
     of safe havens.  Much of this      was crystallized in the Secretary 
     General's 1992 "Agenda for Peace"--which also      stimulated 
     preventative diplomacy/deployments (as in Macedonia) and post      
     conflict peace building to "unfreeze the situation."  His advocacy of 
     a standing         force and better financing are still current 
     issues. 
     
<P>                -  The lessons of Bosnia are many.  Europe's diplomatic 
     disarray lost an   opportunity to influence developments early.  Then 
     there was a large gap between      UN Security Council's commitments 
     and what could be delivered.  For the UN,  there was a loss of 
     peacekeeping credibility and "innocence" as all three parties          
        deceived and manipulated the UN and as peacekeepers became part of 
     the        conflict. UNPROFOR had no capability to counter the adverse 
     propaganda of the  parties.  The key message is that most culprits 
     don't get punished to the  degradation of credibility of the PKO 
     force.
     
<P>               -With respect to reform in the UN, there has been a 
     paralysis--great words     and little action. There remains the 
     critical issue of political will to support PKOs,  a standing force, 
     and financial reform in the UN.
     
<P>                -  For the future, the attitude and actions of the US is 
     critical to the future     utility of peacekeeping.  Preemption can 
     work, but it is not a panacea.     International institutions must be 
     reformed, and the layering and overlap of these    organizations can 
     facilitate situations were there is no center of responsibility and    
        thus nothing is done. There has been a "compliance liability" in 
     agreements that    promotes cheating and almost assures agreements 
     will eventually be unraveled.      The future of peacekeeping is thus 
     mixed. 
     
<P>        b.  Session II, "Peacekeeping-- the European Approach," CAPT 
     Wilson.  He stressed :
     
<P>                -  NATO only does PKOs in areas identified by OSCE.  The US 
     is         ambivalent about the WEU as the European defense pillar of 
     NATO.  The         legitimate involvement of WEU in defense issues is 
     still unclear--but WEU as a        defense entity did participate in 
     the Gulf War (minesweeping operations) and in      the naval blockade 
     of the Balkans.
     
<P>                -  With the Berlin Declaration, there will be a more formal 
     involvement of     the WEU in European defense matters.  The 1992 
     Peaceburg Declaration      earmarked NATO forces for WEU operations.  
     The 1994 Kirchburg Declaration     brought eastern European nations 
     into partnership with the west as associate        members and 
     observers.  The Birmingham Declaration was an agreement to             
        beef up the military capability to include intelligence sharing. 
     
<P>                -  The interlocking European security arrangements can not 
     work without       the US, and it requires the full integration of 
     France.
     
 <P>               -  Europe has yet to act as a corporate body in PKOs.  
     There is much      pressure to act as one, instead of bilaterally as 
     is now the case.
     
 <P>               -  In so-called Peaceburg missions, there has been much 
     talk, but little   substance in meaningful coordination.  Decisions to 
     participate in PKOs are based      on national interests.
     
<P>                -  There is a broader issue of the air and maritime aspects 
     of PKOs.   Logistics and backup has come from the sea.  There is, 
     however, a question of     effective command and control of PKOs by 
     the WEU.  IFOR demonstrated the    possibility of a NATO/non-NATO 
     joint task force (JTF) which worked well.
     
<P>                -  The WEU has also suggested an African pillar for PKOs.  
     There is a         joint French-British paper on this topic for 
     assistance to the OAU.
     
<P>        c.  Session III, "The American Perspective of European 
     Multinational Peacekeeping," was an impromptu presentation which was 
     shaped by the comments of the preceding speakers.  Points that I 
     stressed included:
     
<P>                -   The importance of Europe to the US and its central role 
     in US foreign      policy, as illustrated by our participation in the 
     IFOR operation, our ongoing        commitment to NATO, and the forward 
     positioning        of troops in Europe--the        largest 
     concentration outside the US.
     
<P>                -  The US view of peace operations (POs) in Europe is 
     shaped by our      national strategy of "Engagement and Enlargement" 
     and PDD 25 (briefly        explained). The US doctrinal views of POs 
     was briefly summarized, and the IFOR       operation was   discussed 
     as the nexus of a wide range of PO issues in Europe.
     
<P>                -  Some of the lessons learned from post-Cold War POs 
     include:  the      absolute need for clarity in the mandate; the 
     problems of strategic planning,    especially if there is not a good 
     strategic assessment as the front piece; the value         of the PfP 
     program; the need for agreement on standards and procedures; and the   
        need for the military to understand its need for interface with a 
     variety of non-    military organizations (and the use of CIMIC/CMOCs, 
     PSYOP/PA/Information       campaign, and a plan for dealing with the 
     media).
     
<P>                -  Peace enforcement conducted as a peacekeeping operation, 
     as is the case     with the implementation of the Dayton Accords, 
     offers a new element to    peacekeeping optimized for situations like 
     Bosnia.  The coercion/deterrence   factor of a strong combat 
     capability, and the need for peacekeepers who are well     trained in 
     their combat skills (as well as the specialized expertise useful in 
     PKOs)      has been important to keep the parties in line.  This 
     operation, and its doctrinal       underpinning, is well worth looking 
     at closely by armies well-versed in traditional    peacekeeping in 
     order to remain relevant to the needs of the present and future.
     
 <P>               -  Some of the questions in the Q & A periods were directed 
     at aspects of      our doctrine, the use of PSYOP resources, the US 
     view of operating under non-       US commanders, how the US prepares 
     for PKOs, the attitude of the US military  towards the press, and 
     where do we see peacekeeping going in the next century.</P>

</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<br>
