<center>
<h3>
COMPETITIVE INTELLIGENCE REVIEW
<BR>
</h3>
<h4>Call for Papers<BR>

</h4>
<BR>

</Center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>

December 05 1996<BR><BR>

<p><b><i>Competitive Intelligence Review, </i></b>a quarterly
journal<b><i> </i></b>edited under the auspices of the Society of
Competitive Intelligence Professionals (SCIP) and published by
John Wiley &amp; Sons, is the premier voice of the Competitive
Intelligence profession and the main venue for original material
covering all aspects of the CI field. <b><i>CIR</i></b> is
currently looking for authors to write articles, columns, and
&quot;how to&quot; pieces.</p>


<p><b><i>CIR</i></b>&#146;s readership<b><i> </i></b>understands
the basics of CI, but fresh perspectives are always welcome. Any
innovations involved with your work in CI? Have you had
assignments that might make interesting case studies? Share your
insights and opinions with your fellow CI professionals.</p>

<p align="center"><b><i><u>CIR</u></i></b><u> publishes two types
of papers:</u></p>

<p><b>Articles</b> (at least 2,000 words, or 8-to-10
double-spaced, typed pages) that
contribute to the professional literature and which are
frequently based on 
independent research or in-depth case studies.</p>


<p><b>Departments</b> (usually no longer than 1,500 words, or
4-to-6 typed pages)
that emphasize practical information and which are particularly
useful when
based on the author&#146;s own experiences. Departments can
include concise
case studies, book and software reviews, and recurring columns.</p>


<p align="center"><u>Subject areas include:</u></p>


<p>Competitive Intelligence Competitive Marketing &amp; Sales</p>

<p>Business/Market Intelligence Corporate Security</p>

<p>R&amp;D/Technical Intelligence Information/Knowledge
Management</p>

<p>Strategic Planning New Product/Business Development</p>

<p>Market Research &amp; Analysis Product &amp; Brand Management</p>


<p align="center"><u>Please bear in mind</u>:</p>


<p>The information in your article should be accessible but not
overly basic/introductory. Most of our readers are experienced CI
professionals. The level of information and analysis should address challenges and
situations that readers familiar with CI would find useful and insightful.</p>


<p>Our readers are always interested in concrete examples or case
studies that can serve as a model.</p>


<p>For a sample issue, a copy of our <b>Authors&#146; Guidelines,</b>
or to discuss a topic proposal, please contact Managing Editor Stephen Miller:</p>

<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <p align="center"><b><i>Tel:</i></b> +1 703-739-0696. <b><i>Fax:</i></b><b>
        +</b>1<b> </b>703-739-2524. <b><i>E-mail:</i></b>
        <a href="MAILTO:smiller@scip.org">smiller@scip.org</a><br>
        <b><i>Write:</i></b> SCIP, 1700 Diagonal Road, Suite 520,
        Alexandria, VA 22314.</p>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
