<HEAD><TITLE>

Non-traditional resupply methods/Marines

</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffFF">


<!-- Header/Nav-Bar Table -------------------------------------------->

<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td valign=top width=48>
<a href="mil_c4i.html-ssi"><img width=48 height=68 border=0 src="../../images/back.gif" alt="Back"></a>
</td>
<td valign=top width=48>
<a href="http://www.infowar.com/index.html-ssi"><img width=48 height=68 border=0 src="../../images/home.gif" alt="Home"></a>
</td>
<td valign=top width=48>
<a href="http://www.infowar.com/search_reg.html-ssi"><img width=48 height=68 border=0 src="../../images/srch.gif" alt="Search"></a>
</td>
<td valign=top align=right width=236>
<img border=0 width=236 height=68 src="../../images/line.gif">
</td>

<td width=200>
<img vspace=3 border=0 src="../../images/dot_spac.gif"><br>
<A HREF="http://www.infowar.com/sponsors/sponsors.html-ssi
"><img width=200 height=68 border=0 src="http://www.infowar.com/sponsors/ad4.gif"></A>
</td>
</tr>
</tr>
</table>
<br>
<IMG ALT="[Bomb2]" SRC="../../images/bomb2_li.gif" width=580><p>


<!-- Article Body Table ---------------------------------------------->

<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<img border=0 width=43 height=43 src="../../images/pent.gif">
</td>
<td valign=middle width=440>

</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>

<h3><Center>MARINES EXPERIMENT WITH NON-TRADITIONAL RESUPPLY METHODS FOR SMALL UNITS</H3>

<BR>
</Center>

</table>
<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<td width=440>

December 03, 1996<BR><BR>

<P>INSIDE THE NAVY via Individual Inc. : In an effort to find a way to keep 
small teams of Marines supplied without a large logistical footprint 
ashore, the Commandant's Warfighting Lab, in support of Sea Dragon 
efforts, is looking into several parafoil-based supply delivery systems to 
provide "just-in-time resupply" for troops in the field.
<P>According to Capt. Michael Fernandez, 12-man teams of Marines will operate 
ashore on their own, without resupply, for two to three days at a time. 
These teams will not be resupplied by combat service support groups in the 
traditional sense, where a large supply base is built up on shore 
following an amphibious landing.
<P>"They [supporting elements] will be on ships," Fernandez said. "This is 
the means [parafoils] we plan to use to support the teams ashore from over 
the horizon, they would request supplies that would be delivered directly 
to them, depending on the situation."
<P>Fernandez is the air officer of the combat service support enterprise of 
the Sea Dragon Special Purpose Marine Air-Ground Task Force. He spoke with 
Inside the Navy on Nov. 25.
<P>"All the systems are not your traditional unmanned aerial vehicles (UAV) 
in the sense of having a hard wing," he said. "The UAVs we're looking at 
are based on a parafoil wing, parafoil being a square parachute that can 
be guided."
<P>Guided Parafoil Air Delivery System (GPADS) is one of the systems being 
studied. Fernandez said GPADS is a non-powered, reusable, Global 
Positioning System-guided supply system that "is deployed from an airborne 
platform, either a helicopter or C-130 type cargo aircraft. Once deployed, 
GPADS is programmed to fly certain way points or it can select its own 
course to fly. Once deployed, GPADS acquires GPS satellites required for 
[navigational] tracking, it also takes into account real-time winds and 
then updates its flight profile as best as it can to reach its intended 
impact point."
<P>GPADS was developed at the U.S. Army Natick Research, Development and 
Engineering Center in Natick, MA. It is available in three variants for 
light, medium and heavy loads.
<P>Fernandez said the light version of GPADS is the most appropriate for Sea 
Dragon purposes. It can deliver up from 750 to 1,500 pounds of cargo and 
offers a "precision smart bomb effect in terms of a drop-and-forget 
capability that enhances the ability of the military to respond to a 
broader spectrum of air delivery missions by providing a covert, 
all-weather insertion capability for non-traditional air delivery loads 
such as sensors and munitions," according to a GPADS information paper.
Powered Parafoil, developed by Southwest Research Institute, is another 
GPS-navigated system being looked at. Fernandez said it is essentially a 
fan used to power a swamp boat, attached to a parafoil. "The fan blows air 
aft to inflate the parafoil, while at the same time providing forward 
thrust, together this provides lift." Powered Parafoil requires about 30 
meters for takeoff and is intended to return to its launch point after 
completing its supply run.      
<P>Fernandez told ITN the system was 
originally intended to be landed and off loaded at each supply point, 
however this might not be possible in every clime and place the Marines 
need resupply. Therefore, Fernandez is looking into air-dropping supplies 
from the Powered Parafoil, without the need for the system to land and 
take off several times per run. In concept, Powered Parafoil is intended 
to be launched and recovered by ship. It can carry 500 pounds of cargo, 
and travel up to 200 nautical miles.
<P>A self-deploying GPS-guided glider called Semi-Ridged Deployable Wing 
(SRDW) is also being looked for supply runs. SRDW is deployed from a 
helicopter or cargo aircraft much like the Guided Parafoil. However, 
instead of deploying a parafoil, it uses a semi-ridged glider. Fernandez 
said different power sources for the glider are investigated.
Fernandez said these systems are extremely quiet and nearly impossible to 
detect when operating at night, at least 500 feet above ground.

<P>[11-30-96 at 09:23 EST, Copyright 1996, Inside Washington, File: 
w1129032.4ip]
Entire contents (C) 1996 by INDIVIDUAL, Inc., 8 New England Executive Park 
West, Burlington, MA  01803.</P>

Thank you to Col. G.I. Wilson for submitting.<BR>

</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
