<tr>
<td width=440>

<h3><Center>NEAL OPTIMISTIC ON <BR>MARINE CORPS MODERNIZATION<BR> By John Robinson</H3>

<BR>
</Center>

</table>
<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<td width=440>

December 03, 1996<BR><BR>

<P>DEFENSE DAILY via Individual Inc. -- The Marine Corps' modernization plan 
is "very affordable" and should be able to withstand budget pressures in 
the near term, according to a top general.
<P>"It's a modest program," Gen. Richard Neal, Assistant Commandant of the 
Marine Corps, told Defense Daily in an interview last week.
While he admits that spending levels for Marine Corps ground vehicles have 
been "low" in recent years, Neal believes that issue should "come to 
closure" in 1999. The Marine Corps pays for ground vehicles through its 
own funding line or with "green dollars." Aviation programs are paid for 
in the Navy budget or with "blue dollars."
<P>The Marine Corps has been eager to boost to annual spending on ground 
vehicles to at least $1 billion (Defense Daily, May 4, 1995). This year, 
in FY '97, the Marine Corps has $716.9 million in procurement, its highest 
level in recent years. In FY '94, procurement spending was $441.2 million. 
Procurement spending climbed to $558.6 million in FY '95 and $654.1 
million in FY '96.
<P>With bills for several high ticket aviation programs, such as the V-22 
tiltrotor, coming due around the end of the decade, some observers believe 
the Marine Corps budget could be headed for a train wreck, with a 
disproportionate part of the "blue/green" split going to aviation.
<P>But Neal disagrees. He said that the procurement budget starts to "get well" in FY '99, an 
important year in the development for some of the ground programs, such as 
the Advanced Amphibious Assault Vehicle and the Lightweight 155 millimeter 
howitzer program with the Army.
<P>"We see '99 as a watershed year," he said.
<P>As for fixed wing aviation, the Marine Corps' top requirement is the Joint 
Strike Fighter, which will replace aging AV-8 Harrier jump jets. Neal said 
that the service cannot afford the F/A-18E/F Super Hornet, the Navy's top 
aviation priority. The Navy, which flies the single-seat version of the 
plane, wants the F/A-18E to replace F/A-18C. The Marine Corps flies the 
two-seat F/A-18D, which would be replaced by the F/A-18F.
<P>[11-27-96 at 18:00 EST, Copyright 1996, Phillips Publishing, Inc., File: 
d1127106.4sd]
Entire contents (C) 1996 by INDIVIDUAL, Inc., 8 New England Executive Park 
West, Burlington, MA  01803.</P>


Thank you to Col. G.I. Wilson, OSD  for this submissin.<BR>

</td>

