<!-- Article Body Table ---------------------------------------------->

<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<img border=0 width=43 height=43 src="../../images/class2.gif">
</td>
<td valign=middle width=440>
<center><h2>

 Industrial Espionage Victimizes Company of Revolutionary Internet 
Technology Worth $250 Million (from PRNewswire)

</h2>


</Center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>

<p> <b>AMHERST, N.Y., Aug. 16 /PRNewswire/ </b>-- Technology thieves stole the newest
and fastest entrance ramp to the Information Superhighway.  The loss of what
some are calling the most revolutionary communications system linking consumer
televisions with the Internet is conservatively estimated at $250 million.</P>
    <P>A team of American and Chinese scientists from Interactive Television
Technologies, Inc. (I-TT) were close to completing more than four years of
research and development on the BUTLER, which exponentially increases data
processing speed and eliminates the need for a computer to access the
Internet.</P>
   <P> But someone broke into the company's Amherst, New York, offices between
8:15 and 1O p.m. Tuesday, August 13th and stole items including three
computers containing the plans, schematics, diagrams and specifications for
the BUTLER's technology, plus a number of computer disks with access codes.
However, the thieves left other computer equipment and disks in the office.</P>
    <P>"It had to be industrial espionage," said J. Balan Chirayath, I-TT's
President & CEO.  "The thieves took what they were looking for and then a few
other items just to make it look like a simple burglary."</P>
   <P>The research was done in conjunction with the University at Buffalo and
visiting professors from the People's Republic of China.  Coincidentally, the
company moved the research from an office on Capen Boulevard in Tonawanda
because of security concerns.  They were in temporary offices until
renovations to the company's new high-security office building were complete.</P>
    <P>"This project has been kept top secret from day one because of its
commercial potential," said Steven M. Cohen, I-TT's corporate counsel.
"Unscrupulous companies would pay millions for the technology and prototype to
make hundreds of millions in profit."</P>
    <P>The BUTLER would allow anyone in the world who can operate a television
to:  access World Wide Web, send or receive e-mail, purchase and pay for goods
and services, control inventory, obtain or transmit health care information,
medical insurance claims, and execute other business and personal transactions
without leaving the comfort of their easy chair.</P>
   <P> Similarly, I-TT can utilize this technology with existing cable and
satellite systems to provide everyone simple two-way worldwide communications,
on a real-time chat basis similar to what's currently available using standard
telephone lines.</P>
    <P>The BUTLER looks like a cable television box that can be connected to any
television.  It was developed to allow even computer illiterates to access the
Internet, without the hours of training necessary to master the intricacies of
computers and software.  Now any individual who can operate a television set
could use this technology.</P>
   <P> The company will reconstruct its four years of research using data that
was backed up at the end of July.  However, it now will be forced to apply for
a patent on the technology ahead of their scheduled time frame.</P>
  <P>  The company must also accelerate talks with several strategic partners.</P>
  <P>  "Protecting our brainchild is our top priority," Chirayath said.  "I-TT
will bring this technology to the market, not some thief in the night, I
guaranty that!"</P>
<P>    I-TT, is a New York Corporation, founded in 1996 to provide interactive
television capability to residential and commercial users.  The company's
philosophy is simple, "existing television sets will become the empowering
tools for everyone."</P>

<P>SOURCE Interactive Television Technologies, Inc.</P>
    -0-                         8/16/96<BR>
    /CONTACT: J. Balan Chirayath, President of I-TT, 716-688-6200/<BR>

CO:  Interactive Television Technologies, Inc.<BR>
ST:  New York<BR>
IN:  MLM<BR>
SU:<BR>

<P>Copyright 1996 PR Newswire.  All rights reserved</P>
<BR>

</td>

