<tr>
<td width=440>

<center><H3><BR>
<B>Friendly Fire and TWA Flight 800</B>
<P>
</H3>
</center>
From        ENN Special Report<BR>
11/10/97 - 15:00CST<BR>
<BR>
Part 1

<P>The following is a repost of an earlier article that sheds some light on
the questionable allegations contained in the anonymous Internet post
that was used as "evidence"  in recent statements by Mr. Pierre
Salinger.  We present it here in order to facilitate an open and honest
examination of this tragedy.</P>
==========================================================<BR>
From: RONALD LEWIS    INTELLIGYST@worldnet.att.net<BR>
Subject: DEBUNKING THE TWA FLT 800 "FRIENDLY FIRE" RUMORS<BR>
<BR>
<P>The following is a rebuttal of the absurd "friendly fire" allegations
concerning the loss of TWA FLIGHT 800 which have circulated on the
Internet for months and which recently gained increased notoriety when
they were again espoused by former TV correspondent Pierre Salinger.   I
was asked about this in mid-September and sent my reply out on September
13. This information was posted to at least one discussion news group
covering aspects of the TWA crash, as well as to other parties.  In some
form or another, it should also be available on the Internet but it
seems that a detailed analysis which tears huge gaps in this "theory" of
a "friendly fire" missile hit is not as interesting and sensational as
the rumors being spread.

<P>I invite all interested parties to distribute and disseminate this post
wherever they wish. My name can be left in or taken out, as the user
wishes. Credit for this material is not important-- distribution of the
facts is. Thank you.</P>

Best regards,<BR>
Ron Lewis<BR><BR>

*******************************************************************<BR>

<I>>>From X:    (TO RON LEWIS)<BR>
<BR>
<P>>> What do you think of this one that was forwarded to me?

<P>>>    As an aviator, the language rings true (for instance, "non-beacon
     target (transponder OFF)" sounds like something an ATP would say).

<P>>>     Also, W-105 is south of Long Island ... but on the charts which I
   have (which are old and long expired), the closest warning area to what
   I think is the crash site is W-106
</I>
<P>LEWIS:  If correct, our correspondent does not even have the correct
operating area defined. Not a good start.</P>
<I>
<P>>>     The chief source of my skepticism is the possibility of preventing
     all those sailors from letting the cat out.  There are the familiar
     two chances of keeping this type of thing suppressed: slim and none.
    I would doubt that the Navy would even try, knowing that worse---and
     wider-spread---egg would be on their faces when it inevitably came out.
</I>
<P>LEWIS  This is very correct.  The post I received last evening talked
about three sailors calling home and claiming they had been involved in
an incident resulting in a plane being shot down. Two problems with that
immediately:  Who monitored the phone calls, tallied the count, and knew
they were calls "home." Sounds too pat.  The other problem is that they
did not say they were specifically responsible or knew who was.  As I
related in my lengthy response, I was in Okinawa in September 1983 when
KAL 007 was shot down.  I worked on the F-15 weapons systems and the
F-15s were used to protect US Navy search vessels looking for the black
boxes.  When Soviet aircraft locked on to our ships, "my" F-15s locked
on them in return and chased them away.  The planes were from my wing
and I worked on the weapons. I had flown the same route corridor as 007.
 Therefore, I was "involved" in a shootdown.   In 1985, Delta L-1011
crashed in a wind shear accident at Dallas-Ft. Worth.  Now an imagery
interpreter, I worked on the photos produced of the accident site as
photographed from a 67th Tactical Recon Wing RF-4C.  I was directly
involved in support of the crash investigation, therefore I was
"involved" in the crash, but had no role in causing it.  As such, I
believe that the supposed three crewmen who talked of "being involved"
in TWA 800 may have witnessed it on radar but had absolutely no role in
causing it.   Why have none of these reports been fed to the tabloid
magazines and news shows, by friends and families of these sailors if
not the servicemembers themselves?  It just does not wash.

<P>LEWIS:  The following is the original material (with my rebuttal
commentary later added), received off of the Internet by, that several
parties asked me to evaluate:

<P>Part 2</P>
<I>
<P>>>     Extracted note follows:

<P>>>     The message came to me from a man who was Safety Chairman for the
     Airline Pilots Association for many years and he is considered an
     expert on safety.  He would not ever spread idle rumor.  In short,
    he is usually quite certain before saying anything!

<P>>>     Subject: Friendly Fire?

<P>>>     The following information about TWA Fight 800 was received this
     afternoon: (08-22-96)

<P>>>     TWA flight 800 was shot down by a U.S. Navy guided missile ship which
     was in area W-105.  W-105 is a Warning Area off the SouthEast coast
     off Long Island, and is used by the military for missile firing and
     other military operations
</I>
<P>LEWIS:  A "guided missile ship"?   If our correspondent has such
in-depth information about this incident, why is it that he cannot even
describe the class of ship, its name of hull number.  How about a
specific geographic position as well?</P>
<I>
<P>>>     Guided missile ships travel all over the world defending the US and
    they were conducting practice firings up over the top of a Navy P-3
     radar plane which was on a Southwest heading about over the top of
     TWA 800. Evidently the missile is supposed to go over the top of the
    P-3 and the accuracy of the missile is being measured by
     instrumentation in the P-3
</I>
<P>LEWIS:  A Navy P-3 "radar" plane? The Navy weapons and test labs do have
specially instrumented aircraft but if you wished to monitor the
progress of a missile from a "radar plane", then why not use the E-2C
Hawkeye and give that aircraft's crew additional training in tracking a
missle as well?

<P>US Customs does fly a "radar" version of the P-3 platform known as the
P-3 Airborne Early Warning (AEW) with a radar housing from the E-2
scabbed on the upper rear fuselage of a P-3. It would not be a player.

<P>Theoretically, it is possible that another version, an EP-3A or EP-3J
from VAQ-33 at NAS Key West could have been involved in providing ECM
jamming to test the fleet defenses of TICONDEROGA or ARLEIGH BURKE
ships.  It is POSSIBLE that such jamming could cause an SM-2MR Standard
missile to lose guidance in a heavy ECM environment and go after another
target, but there are several problems with this particular stretch of
the theoretical.

<P>For one thing, the Standard is a semi-active homing missile.  It follows
the radar reflections from the ship to ride to its intended target.
Unless the jammed radar was now focused on TWA 800, what radar
reflections would it be following in a heavily-jammed enviroment?
Secondly, there are reports of several missiles fired.  Finally, and
this is the BIGGEST nay-sayer against a Navy missile being involved.
The range of the SM-2MR Standard missile is 40nm.  At 40nm, under
lighting conditions as those noted that night, the massive flash of
flame from the launchers and the reflection of the flame off of the
resulting plume and cloud of smoke (which is incredibly substantial)
would have been seen for miles around.  The reports I have seen about
strikes of light indicate that they traveled UP toward the 747.  If
fired 40nm away from the target, or anywhere near a distance substantial
enough to put the ship out of sight of numerous witnesses, the SM-2MR
would have been flying almost horizontally or at a very shallow
depression angle. Reports I've seen indicate near-vertical streaks or at
least those approaching 45 degrees or better.  Also, I have not seen any
mention of columns or plumes of smoke being noticeable.  The SM-2MR is
norticeably smoky, sometimes incredibly so.

<P>Where did this "P-3 radar" aircraft originate from?  Why was this a
night launch?  The combat information center of a modern Aegis-equipped
TICONDEROGA-class cruiser or ARLEIGH BURKE-class destroyer is deep in
the bowels of the ship.  It is not as though they can "see" their target
visually. Night or day would not matter in the exercise but daytime
would give range safety a better chance of avoiding such a conflict with
civilian traffic if such is even likely to have occurred.

<P>When somebody says "evidently" something is "supposed to" do anything,
it immediately red-flags this as an issue the author is NOT an expert
in, or even seems well aware of.  It smacks of second-hand information
or rumor.

<P>I also object to a missile "going over the top of the P-3."  If there is
any danger of a loss of tracking on the missile, the P-3 would be too
close for safety's sake.  Besides, you don't simply let a missile fly
loose and watch what it does.  A surface-to-air missile is supposed to
lock on a target such as a drone.  If an EP-3A/J was involved in
jamming, it would likely have jammed the radars to the point that they
could not lock on to a target and there would have been no point in
firing a missile at all.  There is no mention of drone targets, again
indicating that the author either does not have familiarity with the
subject matter or has not checked all of his facts.</P>
<I>
<P>>>     There was a USAir flight coming from the Southeast descending towards
     Providence, RI that had been cleared to 21,000 feet and the TWA 800
     aircraft was restricted to 13,000 feet.  The air traffic controller
     requested the USAir flight to turn on his landing lights with the
     idea that TWA might see his lights and identify him.  At that point, he
    would clear the TWA flight to continue his climb.
</I>
</P>LEWIS:  Numerous eyewitnesses, including civilian and military pilots
aboard commercial airliners saw what they report as missile activity.
Any shipboard missile launch that could not be seen from land because of
the over-the-horizon curvature of the earth would not have been hidden
from people flying in aircraft.  SOMEBODY would have seen the extremely
bright flash, brightly-lit plume of smoke, and the flame of the missile
exhaust if this had been a ship-launched missile.  They didn't.  It
wasn't.</P>
<I>
<P>>>     The P-3 was a non-beacon target (transponder OFF) flying southwest in
     the controlled airspace almost over TWA 800 and made NO calls to ATC.
     After the explosion, he continued his flight to the west and then
     called ATC and asked if they would like him to turn around and assist
     with the "accident!"
</I>
<P>LEWIS:  A P-3 as a "target."  OK.  Let's assume this is a "dry-fire"
exercise in which the crew is to lock on to a target and simulate
launching a missile.  Otherwise, the P-3 and its crew are going to be
splashed.  So, how is it a live missile gets launched?   And, note the
description of "controlled airspace."  What does that mean?  Controlled
by whom?  Exercise safety officers? FAA air traffic controllers?
"Controlled" airspace indicates to me that somebody should have
controlled the 747 and kept it out of such "controlled" airspace around
an exercise.  Besides, such exercises are not held in secret but are
published in NOTAMs (Notices to Airmen and Mariners, if I am not
mistaken).  So, why hasn't anybody at regional air traffic control
centers or the JFK tower talking about this murderous Navy assault that
supposedly took place?  Because it DIDN'T happen!

<P>Yes, I know that accidents have happened, such as the carrier a few
years back that was supposed to simulate the launch of radar-guided Sea
Sparrow missiles and, through an error and failure to follow procedure,
they fired a live missile--or two--at a Turkish destroyer nearby. The
missile homed in on the ship's radar array and struck the bridge below,
killing the ship's captain and I believe at least one other officer.
Things do happen.

<P>But let me take a moment to interject something here.  Let's suppose,
just for argument's sake, that this was a deadly "friendly fire"
exercise that went awry.  Fine.  You have to really stretch to assume
that over 300 crewmen are going to keep silent forver.  Then you have
the P-3 crew. OK, so they're all Navy and they'll all cover this
incident up because, being Navy personnel, they are all lobotomized
robot types with no conscience and no concern for the 230 victims and
their families.  What about the Air National Guard officers and men in
the two HH-60Gs and lone HC-130P?  What allegiance do they owe to the
allegedly pirate-ridden, corrupt and evil Navy? Nothing.</P>

<P>>> You will remember that the first announcement about this accident=
 came from the Pentagon.  The spokesman mentioned that they were sending=
 the Navy to the crash site.  They immediately sent a Navy Captain who was
 replaced the next day by an Admiral.  That Admiral is still on the scene.

<P>LEWIS:  This is making a mountain range out of a sand pile.  The
military happened to be on the scene because the Air National Guard was
practicing night rescue missions in the area and reported the accident.
The P-3 crew deployed numerous rafts  (by the way, if I'm not mistaken,
specially outfitted jamming EP-3s do not have sufficient space for as
many rafts but we'll have to confirm that).  Of course the Pentagon
would be the first agency to release information because their rescue
aircraft were first on the scene and they had the most information
available.  What is so sinister about that?

<P>Now, the next part is very interesting because the post I received last
night on TWA rumors had this admiral going out to relieve the skipper of
the ship that supposedly shot down TWA 800. What the above correspondent
is telling me is nothing more than the fact that a senior naval officer
wasappointed, possibly to head up rescue and recovery efforts contributed
to by the Navy (it was an accident at sea, you understand) and, the next
day, the Navy was able to re-arrange the schedule of an admiral and send
the flag officer to replace him.  That only makes sense from a military
procedures standpoint.  Note, however, how this story was twisted in the
rumor mill and made to sound as though the skipper of the launching ship
was replaced by an admiral.  Simply amazing how these transformations
occur in the re-telling!</P>
<I>
<P>>>     The FBI has conducted at least 3,000 eyewitness interviews and the
     NTSB has not been able to be a part of these interviews not have any
     access to the contents of them.  Some of those eyewitnesses reported
     seeing lights.  Those were probably the landing lights of the USAir
     plane.
</I>
<P>LEWIS:   Who says, with such authority, that the NTSB has been barred.
Let's see some dates, some names, some more specifics.  This entire
document is riddled with such generalities and no specifics that can be
independently verified.  So the FBI performed 3,000 interviews.  They
were part of a criminal probe.  The NTSB was admittedly so outnumbered
and short-handed that they probably declined to participate in such
interviews on the assumption that the physical evidence would tell them
all they needed.  Why spread out limited assets by running around the
countryside accompanying hundreds of FBI agents.  The NTSB is a very
small agency and not=
well-funded.</P>
<I>
<P>>>     It has been a cover-up from the word go.  The NTSB is there in name
     ONLY.  All announcements made by Mr. Bob Francis say absolutely
     nothing and notice that the FBI is always standing beside or behind
     Mr. Francis and it would appear that his job is to make sure that
     nothing is said that would give away  "THE BIG SECRET!"
</I>
<P>LEWIS:  Oh, it would "appear" that Kallstrom has a certain function, all
right.  Can you spell S-P-E-C-U-L-A-T-I-O-N.   This is highly subjective
opinion based in no concrete fact.  Mr. Francis does seem to have
carefully selected his words when describing his findings but this may
be attributable to nothing more diabolical than his style of speech.
Rather than saying "absolutely nothing", he has often described the
condition of the debris, where charring has been noted, the percentage
of wreckage recovered, locations of the suspected seat of the explosion,
and so on. Investigators like those of the NTSB do not like to make wild
and speculative comments. They are very methodical and plodding in their
procedural manner.  To those who do not understand this approach, their
slow and deliberate delivery may seem to be an attempt to hide or cover
up things.  I am really surprised that a person identified as having
anything to do with expertise in airline safety would not realize this
from direct experience.  That alone makes me wonder if this person
really does have the credentials presented.</P>

<I>
<P>>>     It is time to end this farce and tell the public the real truth as to
     what happened to TWA 800.  My source shall remain my own but the=
     above information is true and I believe it will all become known soon,
     now that all of you know the real truth.
</I>
<P>LEWIS:  This is author is unwilling to provide sources.  There are few,
if any, specifics.  No detailed names, ship types, classes, hull numbers
or designations of the aircraft, ships and missiles involved, other than
P-3, and that aircraft was improperly described as a "radar" platform.
The "true information" alluded to here is suspect and there is little
real "information" provided.  The entire post seems to be an
amalgamation of hearsay, second-hand information and beliefs rather than
hard evidence, solid fact or reasoned conclusions.

<P>As I outlined earlier in relating the Turkish destroyer strike, there is
nothing which indicates that an accident could not have happened.
Nobody seems to know for absolute certain.  I will advise you of one
other thing, though, which I believe is highly relevant: within the
first 24 hours after this incident occurred, an Iranian based in London
and known as an official propagandist for the Tehran government was
announcing that this was the result of a "friendly fire" missile strike.
 No specifics.  No identification of missile type, launch platform,
etc., just that it was the result of a missile strike.  His certainty in
the face of such total uncertainty and confusion by all of the
eyewitnesses, rescue workers, pilots and so on, convinced me, at a very
early stage, that this was no accident and that the missile fired was
not "friendly."  Nothing since has made me waver in that belief.  If any
Navy shot down TWA Flt 800, I would look for a seaman or officer of the
Iranian Navy manning an ocean-capable cabin cruiser or other such small
vessel off the coast of the United States on the night of July 17,
1996.=20

<P>LEWIS SUMMATION: Again, I was not an eyewtiness to this event, a
participant in it, or a member of any of the agencies involved in
witnessing it, investigating it, or allegedly causing it.  I have made
my assessments based on military training as an imagery interpreter and
intelligence analyst with access to open-source reports relating to the
loss of TWA.  My comments are based on in-depth study, some personal
experience with the weapons and platforms described and certified
expertise in recognizing the characteristics of ships, aircraft and
missile.

<P>I invite comments and rebuttal from all interested parties but I ask
that all objections or counter-arguments be presented with specific data
such as specific date and time of day, identification of ship class,
name, type and hull number, descriptions of colors, angles of attack and
characteristics of any aircraft or missiles noted.  The author of the
above post has much more work to do in order to present a credible
argument.  In the absence of that additional effort, I can only rate the
above information as a poorly-researched, uninformed, speculative,
subjective, opinionated and second-hand hypothesis.  I would not even
given it the added weight of describing it as a "theory."

<P>At your service,

<P>Ronald W. Lewis, CHIEF MILITARY & AVIATION ANALYST, THE INTELLIGYST
GROUP</P>


</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
