<tr>
<td width=440>

<center><H3>D E S T A<BR>
Destabilization, Terrorism & Disinformation
</H3>
<BR>
</center>



A Northern Newsletter of Threat Analysis<BR>
<BR>
Volume IV, No.4<BR>
September - October 1996<BR>
<BR>
Editor: Mr. Bertil Haggman, P.O.Box 1412, <BR>
S-25114 HELSINGBORG SWEDEN<BR>
E-mail: bertil.haggman@helsingborg.se<BR>
<HR>

IN THIS ISSUE<BR>

Russian Provocation I<BR>
Russian Provocation II <BR>
Disinformation in the Palme Case  <BR>
Communist Party Leader Alcoholic<BR>
<HR>

<P>NEW IMPORTANT SOURCE ON INFOWAR

<P>Infowar wizard Winn Schwartau has a new webpage on
Information Warfare and Information Security. It is
the ultimate for those who want to stay in the picture
in this important field. Try http://www.infowar.com. but
do it soonest.

<P>RUSSIAN PROVOCATION I - TWO SWEDISH *SPIES* ARRESTED

<P>In the beginning of September the Russian Security Service FSB
reported on the arrest32-year old Peter Nordstroem for espionage in St.
Petersburg. The arrest was made at the Naval Museum in
Russias second largest city in front of hidden Russian video-
cameras. The pictures were later shown on Russian television. In
the museum building Nordstroem accepted a wooden Russian doll.
In exchange he handed over 2,000 US dollars. A Russian counter-
intelligence officer was interviewed on TV claiming that Swedish
espionage in Russia had increased. It is the first arrest of a
Swedish spy in modern time in Russia or the Soviet Union.

<P>The Russian Security Service leaked the story to the newspaper
Nezavizimaya Gazeta and to the privately owned TV-station NTV.

<P>Nordstroem came to Russia already on 21 February this year. He 
entered on a visa that expired on 1 March. The Russians claim 
that he represented a company that was created by the Swedish 
Defense Staff for the purpose of espionage. Nordstroem was briefed,
according to Russian media, at the Swedish General Consulate
in the city *on the espionage situation*.

<P>The Russians claim Nordstroem planned the meeting carefully.
The arrest was made in front of a videocamera. Three Russians
rushed the Swede and his Russian contact, handcuffed them and
took them away.

<P>On TV the doll was shown to contain a role of unexposed film.
The Russian contact is accused of having had at least ten contacts
with Swedish military intelligence. The spokesman for FSB, Sergey 
Gorlenko, said that Swedish intelligence lately had shown increasing
interest in the Russian Navy, but also in the situation in Caucasus.
But the Swedish agents according to Gorlenko also have an interest in
the Ural and Volga regions.

<P>One can wonder why FSB waited as long as six months before leaking
the news of the incident to media ?

<P>The spy accusation led to a Swedish diplomat having to leave Moscow
earlier than planned. However, Nordstroem had between 1989 and 1995 
worked for the Swedish Defense Research Establishment. He now was
employed by the Celsius Tech Corporation involved in the most
secret defense equipment project in Sweden, the missile protection
of the new Swedish jet fighter JAS Griffin.

<P>Later in September another Swede living in Gothenburg was accused
in Russian media for espionage in the city of Pskov, believed in
Sweden to be the staging point for a possible future Russian invasion.
It is the center for the airborne troops in Northwest Russia.

<P>Four possible theories for the FSB action in September have been 
put forward by intelligence experts:

<P>- It is a war between KSI, the secret Swedish intelligence organization,
  and the Russian FSB. KSI might have carried out several succesful
  operations and FSB now wanted to break the trend.

<P>- It is a revenge action for the deportation of the Russian spy
  Michail Smirnov from Sweden in April 1995.

<P>- FSB is seeking a larger budget and wants to show its muscles for
  the Russian administration and the State Duma.

<P>- It is an attempt to interfere with the cooperation between the
  littoral countries of the Baltic Sea. The Nordstroem affair was 
  revealed the same day US mediator Richard Holbrooke arrived in
  Stockholm to discuss Baltic cooperation.

<P>Your editor believes in the last theory. The Russians are angry over
Sweden leaving its policy of non-alliance and moving towards a
closer cooperation with the United States.</P>

RUSSIAN PROVOCATION II - DID THE RUSSIAN<BR>
CRUISER SHOOT DOWN A SWEDISH FIGHTER ?<BR>

<P>Latvian naval officers on 16 October claimed that the
Swedish jet fighter that crashed in the water near
the new Russian nuclear missile cruiser *Peter the
Great* was shot down. Earlier the Swedish Air Force Staff
believed it was an accident but the new theory will also
be tested in the investigation.

<P>The facts are that the Russians were making a test run
with the cruiser around 30 nautical miles outside the
Latvian coast. Two Latvian patrol vessels were watching the
Russians.

<P>Two Swedish Viggen fighters were flying low near the cruiser
to take photographs. Suddenly a Russian reconnaissance aircraft
appears in front of the Swedish planes and they attempt to
pass under it. During this manuever one of the Swedish pilots
crashed into the water. He never had time to eject himself from
the plane.

<P>Latvian officers aboard the patrol vessels claim that there was
an intense radio traffic between the Russian vessels which was
suddenly broken off and followed by firing and flames were seen
from the Swedish Viggen that went down. The other pilot managed
to get away and return to base.

<P>Later Russian media claimed that the Swedish fighters were training
mock attacks against the cruiser, which has been denied by the
Swedish Air Force. The Latvians underlined the importance of Sweden
salvaging the wreckage of the plane to find evidence of the Russian
shots.

<P>The latest incident could be another attempt by the Russians to tell
Sweden that they are unhappy about Swedish-American cooperation in
what Moscow believes is its backyard.</P>

DISINFORMATION IN THE PALME CASE<BR>

<P>Late in September South African Colonel Eugene de Kock revealed
in the Supreme Court in Pretoria, where he is standing trial, that
he knew that the assassination of Olof Palme, the Swedish Premier,
in February 1986, was planned by the South African intelligence
officer Craig Williamson.

<P>De Kock is standing trial accused of a number of s.c. hit squad
assassinations in South Africa during the 1980s and 1990s.

<P>Another hit squad officer, Dirk Coetzee, later said that the
actual shooting of Palme in Stockholm was carried out by a 
former member of the Rhodesian Selous Scouts, Anthony White,
now living in Mocambique.

<P>Yet another South African intelligence operative claimed
that the assassin was a Swede living on Northern Cyprus.
Other sources indicated it was a Turk hired by the South
Africans to do the shooting.

<P>The reason for the assassination of Palme was claimed to be that
he was an active opponent of apartheid and that ANC was 
supported by Swedish funds.

<P>One of the reasons for this explosion of allegations is of
course that some of the officers are standing trial or are
risking prosecution. One opportunity to be pardoned is
to tell as much as possible for the s.c. Truth and Reconciliation 
Commission.

<P>The main suspect in Sweden is a man that was sentenced for the
crime in lower court, Christer Pettersson. He was picked out in
a police line-up by the only witness, Mrs. Palme. No murder weapon
has been found and with the identification by Mrs. Palme it will
be hard indeed for the police to even get a prosecution of an
alleged South African suspect.

<P>Other possibilities through the years have been PKK, the Kurdish
terrorist organization, Iranian intelligence and the former KGB.

<P>De Kock says he has no first hand information and that he will
tell all before the Commission when his trial is over.

<P>Meanwhile the game of disinformation continues. After ten years it is
not likely the assassin will ever be convicted.</P>

SWEDENS MILITARY INTELLIGENCE ORGANIZATION<BR>

<P>MUST (Militaera underraettelse- och sakerhetstjaensten), Swedish Military
intelligence, is led by Major General Erik Rossander.

<P>He leads seven sections: the Command Section under Colonel Haakan
Petterson. The Analysis Section is headed by Colonel Mats Engman.
Naval Commander Mats Haglund is head of Operations and Lt. Colonel
Johan Edstroem heads Military Forces Section. Security and Protection
is the responsibility of Naval Captain Erland Soennerstedt and
responsible for diplomatic contacts is the Military Attache Section.
The Office for Special Investigation (KSI) is the top secret section of 
MUST.</P>

SERB FROM SWEDEN CHEATED KARADZIC<BR>

<P>One of the main supporters of suspected war criminal Radovan Karadzic
has been a Serb living in Sweden, Brank Ostojic.

<P>He is now suspected of cheating the Bosnian Serb Republic of around
10 million US dollars. Ostojic became Swedish citizen in 1983 and 
belonged to the inner circle of Bosnias most wanted man. Ostojic 
is believed to have purchased weapons for the Bosnian Serbs in 
Copenhagen, Denmark, for large amounts.

<P>He has been a resident of Moscow during the latest months but his 
official residence is Malmoe, Sweden.

<P>Ostojic was made Vice Premier and also Minister of Finance and
Industry for his help of the Serbs in Bosnia. The Pale *government*
now accuses Ostojic of a multimillion embezzlement in connection
with an oil deal.</P>

COMMUNIST PARTY LEADER IN SWEDEN ALCOHOLIC<BR>

<P>Mrs. Gudrun Schyman, leader of the Left Party in Sweden, with around
12 percent of the electorate in the latest polls, had recently to
be treated for alcoholism. It happened after she used a movie theater
as public bathroom during the showing of a film.

</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
