<tr>
<td width=440>

<center><H3>HOW THE CIA COMBATS INTERNATIONAL TERRORISM ..
</H3>
<BR>
</center>

By Steve Macko, ENN Editor<BR>
<BR>

<P>U.S. Central Intelligence Agency Director John Deutch recently
gave a speech at Georgetown University in Washington that offered
some insight on how the CIA is working against international
terrorism.

<P>According to Deutch, the principal threats are radical Islamic
fundamentalist groups, such as the Iranian-backed Hezbollah,
the Egyptian al-Gama'a al-Islamiya, HAMAS and others.  These
groups use terrorism as their only way to battle democratic
institutions.  Deutch warned that these groups are considered
to be a growing threat.

<P>To offset these terrorist organizations, the U.S. intelligence
community established the Counterterrorist Center in 1986.  The
CTC reports directly to the DCI and is designed to bring all
elements of the intelligence community together to collect and
analyze information from all over the world about terrorists and
their organizations.  Information such as how terrorists train
and operate is collected, as well as who supports them and where
they may hide.

<P>Professional officers from ten different agencies are part of the
CTC.  They come from the CIA, the National Security Agency, the
Defense Intelligence Agency, the Federal Bureau of Investigation,
the U.S. State Department and others.  These officers work together
to provide a "strategic warning" about terrorists who may be
planning to strike at United States interests inside or outside
of the country.

<P>In Deutch's opinion, the CTC is the best organization, of its type,
in the world.  If another nation has better information about a
specific terrorist threat, the CTC will seek access to that
information through liaison relationships.

<P>The Director said that President Clinton instructed him to increase
intelligence efforts against the terrorist threat.  Recently, the
CIA has implemented a four-point program to comply with the
directive:

<P>-- A national-level foreign Terrorism Warning Group was created
within the CTC.  This group is made up of experts who will focus
their efforts to review intelligence from all sources and will
provide warning of possible terrorist attacks against U.S. interests
and facilities.

<P>-- A significant number of additional CIA Directorate of Operations
case officers have been deployed overseas and are assigned to the
CTC to work against foreign terrorism.

<P>-- Intelligence support for force protection has been expanded
for military facilities.  An example of this would be the use
of National Intelligence Support Teams.  Currently, there are
seven such teams that are assisting the U.S. military in the
Balkans and in Saudi Arabia.

<P>-- The U.S. intelligence community will increase its capability
to act forcefully against terrorists worldwide.  More options
will be given to the President to preempt and disrupt and defeat
any known terrorist plans.

<P>There recently was a worldwide anti-terrorism conference that
was held in Fort Walton Beach, Florida.  Counterterrorism
experts who attended that conference said that reacting to
terrorist attacks is not the way to combat the attacks themselves.
Most experts said that there must be a long-term, continuing
effort to improve and sustain security around U.S. interests.

<P>The vice chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, U.S. Air Force
General Joseph W. Ralston. said that recent terrorist attacks
have not been isolated incidents.  Ralston said, "We need to
put aside the notion that terrorism is a series of unfortunate,
one-time events to be dealt with on a case-by-case basis."

<P>"We have emerged in the last decade as the first target of
international terrorism for a host of political, economic,
geopolitical reasons," said Winston Wiley, the chief of the
CIA's Counterterrorist Center.

<P>Wiley believes that future attacks will be conducted with more
advanced unconventional weapons.  Terrorists will probably
attempt to use nuclear, chemical or biological materials.
Wiley said, "As the decade evolves, I think we're going to
see some movement in that direction."</P>

</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
