<tr>
<td width=440>

<center><H3>Deputy Attorney General speaks on computer terrorism
</H3>
<BR>
</center>

By Steve Macko, ENN Editor<BR>
<BR>

<P>WASHINGTON (ENN) - Deputy U.S. Attorney General Jamie S. Gorelick on
Friday spoke at a forum that was sponsored by the Council on Foreign
Relations.  Ms. Gorelick, said that there is a high potential of
crippling strikes aimed at vital U.S. computer and/or energy systems by
terrorists.

<P>"One of our most important challenges in the coming years will be
battling terrorists at home and abroad," said Gorelick.  She added that
the United States could respond to the attacks with various options that
range from "intelligence collection to military options."

<P>Gorelick also said that the U.S. must defend itself against terrorists
who have the potential to "wreck havoc with little investment of time or
money or personal risk."  According to Gorelick, terrorist attacks since
1993 have decreased by about 20 percent, but Americans remain the prime
target of international terrorists.

<P>She added in her speech, that the U.S. government should take  "a very
aggressive response" and should implement the future recommendations of
a presidential commission that call for "hardening vital infrastructure
against computer and physical attacks."

<P>In closing, Gorelick said, "Our national well-being rests on an
increasingly interconnected infrastructure ... our power grids, our
telecommunications, our banking system, gas and oil pipelines and
transportation system are increasingly linked together."</P>

                                  ***<BR>
10/11/96<BR>

<P>Greek NATO Officer's Car Bombed

<P>An explosion in Athens late on Thursday night destroyed the parked car
of a Greek Air Force officer connected with NATO, prompting speculation
that it may be the beginning of a new wave of terrorist strikes. No one
was injured.

<P>The car was parked on the road at the intersection of Keas and
Kithairionos streets near the house of the officer in the densely
populated district of Kypseli, a police spokesman said. The owner was
identified as Greek Air Force Colonel Antonis Roussos, 49, who, until
recently, was serving at the NATO base in Naples, Italy, home to the
military alliance's Mediterranean air wing. Roussos is one month away
from retirement.

<P>According to police reports, a time-bomb was used in the explosion -
similar to the devices used by the November 17 terrorist group during
the 70's. There was no claim of responsibility but the anti-terrorist
squad did not rule out that November 17 or another terrorist group, such
as the Revolutionary People's Struggle (ELA), were behind the attack.


<P>The explosion, at 11 p.m., destroyed the front of Roussos' Mercedes
which had the licence plate number AFI-N58917 and also displayed
assorted military stickers. The explosion also damaged a car parked
nearby and shattered the windows of several neighboring buildings. "When
we heard the explosion we immediately thought of the car", the officer's
wife Vasso said. Roussos said he had not received threats from anyone at
any time. Small anarchist groups often use homemade explosive devices to
damage vehicles belonging to officials of Western countries or
organizations to stress their opposition to Greece's membership of NATO
and the European Union.
(Part 1 of 3)</P>

</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
