<tr>
<td width=440>

<center><H3>DOD's Anti-Terrorism Conference/FtlWalton Beach, FL
</H3>
<H4>from ENN:</H4><BR>
<BR>
</center>



<P>
PRESS RELEASE - 10/14/96<BR>
American Forces Press Service<BR>

<P>Reacting after a terrorist attack  is not the way to combat terrorist
attacks, according to officials at DoD's recent worldwide anti-terrorism
conference at Fort Walton Beach, Fla. Combating the threat of attack
requires a long-term, continuing effort to improve and sustain security
for U.S. personnel and facilities, the experts said.

<P>DoD and other federal officials and civilian law enforcers discussed the
need to change people's mindset on anti-terrorism. Officials said they
need to break the cycle of being complacent when there are no attacks
and then developing a "hunker down" response after terrorist attacks
occur.

<P>Recent attacks are not isolated incidents, according to Air Force Gen.
Joseph W. Ralston, vice chairman, Joint Chiefs of Staff. "We need to put
aside the notion that terrorism is a series of unfortunate, one-time
events to be dealt with on a case by case basis," he said.

<P>Winston Wiley, chief of the CIA's Counterterrorist Center in Washington
said "We have emerged in the last decade as the first target of
international terrorism for a host of political, economic, geopolitical
reasons," Future attacks will take advantage of the world's advanced
weapons technology, he said. Conventional, semi-smart and smart weapons
systems are becoming increasingly available in the world marketplace.
Terrorists may also concoct crazy cocktails of nuclear, biological and
chemical materials. "As the decade evolves I think we're going to see
some movement in that direction," Wiley said.

<P>Terrorists will also take advantage of advances in information
technology, Wiley said. "It is not that terrorists are out in front of
the rest of society," he said. "It's simply that they are going along
taking advantage of the increasing number of communications systems,
transportation systems, public encryption and the like. That fits
naturally into their kit bag."

<P>Conference working groups said more funding, better training and a
clearly defined chain of responsibility are needed to ensure a
consistent, sustainable force protection program, DoD officials said.
The United States also needs better intelligence sharing and to develop
a national policy detailing interagency responsibilities. DoD, the Joint
Staff and the unified combatant commanders are now focused on reducing
the vulnerability of U.S. personnel and facilities.  The fiscal 1998
budget will include money specifically appropriated for force
protection.</P>

                       *****Fire/EMS News*****<BR>

<P>(Prague, Czechlosavakia) Prague fire officials are reporting a major
subway incident today, in which as many as thirty people may have been
injured. Smoke filled the central section of the underground train
system and forced a cessation of operations at approx. 10:00a.m.
(local). As many as thirty people may have suffered smoke inhalation
injuries as they were evacuated from the tunnel. Several were taken to
local hospitals, but no further information on their condition was made
available.  No cause of this incident was immediately determined and it
is said to be under investigation.</P>

