<tr>
<td width=440>

<center><H2> DISTURBING "DEJA ENTENDU"AND "DEJA VU</H2>
<H2>by John Dermaut</H2>


</center>
<P>"Terrorism is the security challenge of the 21st century."  British
Prime Minister John Major.<BR>

<P>1. Tough talk alone does not work.  Besides, it is all "Deja entendu"
(heart that before...).</P>
<A NAME="arabia"></A>
<P>On August 2, 1996, Defense Secretary William Perry warned any nation
linked to the <A HREF="#Point1">bombing of U.S. troops in Saudi
Arabia</A> of "<B>strong action</B>."  Secretary Perry also said that
there are several different groups in the Gulf region that the U.S. was
watching closely and that even included some domestic groups in the
desert Kingdom.  Some 20,000 American troops are stationed in the
Persian Gulf to defend American "vital interests" and to maintain the
flow of the liquid gold.  Four thousand of those troops will be moved to
"safer places" because the terrorist threat continues to exist.  That
move will cost more than $200 million, of which Saudi Arabia will pay
half.  It is no secret that certain groups want the U.S. out of the Gulf
region altogether.  Secretary Perry said: "<B>We cannot let them
succeed</B>."  Perry ordered 700 dependents to leave Saudi
Arabia....</P>

<P>It is very interesting to note that the speaker of the House, Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga., in an interview mentioned two countries: Syria and Iran
but not Libya.  He stated: "We are the most powerful nation in the world
and the message we should send to Syria, Iran and similar countries is,
"<B>you mess with us and you will be severely damaged</B>."  He also
said that if necessary "<B>decisive action</B>" will be taken.</P>

<P>Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, stated that if Iran was involved in the
bombing, "<B>we're going to have to get tough</B>."  Sen. Joseph Biden,
D-Del., went even further and said that if the bombing was supported by
a state, it would be "<B>an act of war</B>."</P>

<P>As far as the investigation into the bombing, FBI Director Louis
Freeh found the Cooperation with the local officials "<B>good</B>." But,
he said, it needs improvement...</P> 
<A NAME="panam"></A>
<P>On August 5, 1996, President Clinton called Libya and Iran "two of
the most dangerous supporters of terrorism in the world."  He also
stated that  "<B>the United States will bring to justice any terrorists
who attack the United Sates or U.S. citizens</B>."  President Clinton
will sign a bill that would punish foreign companies investing in Iran's
or Libya's energy sector.  That bill is already being criticized by
Canada, Mexico, China, Russia and most of the European countries, all of
whom indicate they will not go along with it.  The measure would impose
sanctions on foreign firms that invest $40 million or more in a year in
the energy sector of either Iran or  Libya.  Clinton was joined by
relatives of victims of the in 1988 downed <A HREF="#Point2">Pan Am
103</A>.</P>

<P>Terrorists get concerned during an election year because each
political parties wants to look tougher than the other.  The most
difficult part is when one of the parties gets elected and has to
deliver results.  That is when terrorists can resume their
activities.</P>

<P>Both Iran and Libya are on the State Department's list of countries
that sponsor terrorism.  Iran accuses the U.S. of pointing a finger at a
soft and convenient target and stated that the U.S. should either "shut
up" or produce evidence to back the allegations.  Iranian officials also
claim that by constantly accusing Iran, the terrorist groups around the
globe will have a free ride because no matter who plants bombs, Iran
will always be blamed and the real perpetrators will escape justice.</P>

<P>Germany and some other countries ask why both Syria and Saudi Arabia
are not on the proposed sanctions list. </P> 

<P>During questioning by Israeli authorities, an Islamic militant named
Hassan Salameh, admitted that he was trained in Iran and Sudan.  Salameh
is accused of illegal possession of explosives and of assisting suicide
bombers. </P> 

<P>Osama Bin Laden has been linked to terrorist activities, according to
the U.S. Department of State.  Laden allegedly is one of the most
significant sponsors worldwide of Islamic fundamentalist activities,
which range from funding recruitment centers in Egypt to sponsoring some
specific terrorist acts.</P>  

<P>Reportedly Iran considered a blockade of the Strait of Hormuz, the
choke point for half of the world's oil.  Europe, Asia and the United
States are its biggest customers.  The largest oil-producers use the
Strait to export the liquid gold.  The equivalent of Europe's daily
consumption, which is about 15 million barrels, passes through there.
</P> 

<P>Then there is Turkey where Necmettin Erbakan became Prime Minister
after the elections in December 1995.  During the campaign, Erbakan
proposed to pull out of NATO, cut ties with Israel, and pushed for an
Islamic Union.  Erbakan has signed a $20 billion agreement with Iran to
buy natural gas for the next 20 years.</P>

<P>Although no country can defeat the US militarily, several
organizations could bring U.S. cities and/or states to their knees
through a sustained campaign of terrorism.  It has been done in overseas
countries.  Let's hope it never happens here.  </P><BR>



<P><B>2. International co-operation...</B>

<P>The G-7 nations and Russia came up with a 25 points plan.  The U.S.
also comes up with plan and this is the nth plan after the nth bombing. 
It is starting to look like a pattern:  once there is a bombing; there
is a plan.  Then some kind of committee is formed.  There is a large
variety to choose from: simple committees, sub-committees, oversight
committees, investigating committees and advisory committees.  The
formed committee can either report to the House, Senate or government
agency.  Or they can choose to all form their own.  A lot of times the
wheel is reinvented over and over again. A recurring thread is the cry
for more cooperation between departments and/or countries, and for the
exchange of more intelligence between departments and/or countries. 
Sanctions of some type are popular, too.  How much cooperation and
exchange of information is really there if after every major bombing
countries keep needing to increase cooperation and exchange of
information ?</P>

<P>In June of 1984 (twelve years ago) a G-7 summit was held in London. 
Already then the participating nations agreed that there was a need for
"closer cooperation between police and security organizations and other
relevant authorities, especially in the exchange of information,
intelligence and technical knowledge."</P>  

<P>Two years later, in May of 1986, another summit was held in Tokyo
where the seven nations urged for "the closest possible bilateral and
multilateral cooperation between police and security organizations and
other relevant authorities in the fight against terrorism."</P>  

<P>In June 1987 they all came together in Venice where the heads of
state were "profoundly aware of our peoples' concern at the threat posed
by terrorism" and they reaffirmed their "determination to combat
terrorism both through national measures and through international
cooperation among ourselves and with others, when appropriate, and
therefore renew our appeal to all like-minded countries to consolidate
and extend international cooperation in all appropriate fora." </P> 

<P>Last year the G-7 and Russia all met in Canada where they concluded
that they were "determined to work together in the international
community, with international organizations, institutions and other fora
to fight terrorism."  With an aim to preventing terrorist acts they
proposed to: "share our technical knowledge, intelligence, forecasts of
threats and activities and information on different tactics and methods,
means of terrorists through closer bilateral and other forms of
co-operation among police and security agencies and other relevant
authorities."</P>  

<P>During the last summit in July 1996, in Paris, the eight countries
came to the conclusion that "in order to harness our own capacities more
tightly we decided to establish among our countries a directory of
counter-terrorism competences, skills and expertise to facilitate
practical cooperation.  The very first subheading under "Adopting
Internal Measures To Prevent Terrorism" is "Improving counter-terrorism
cooperation and capabilities."</P>

<P>The G-7 and now G-8 does not even agree on the spelling of the word
"cooperation" (or is it co-operation) and they are going to stop
terrorism !  It looks like the only ones who benefit from these summits
are the travel agencies, airlines, and caterers.  The other thought was
that it probably would be a better idea to have a summit on learning how
to ski.  It would save more lives than the summits on terrorism do.</P>

<P><B>3. Deja vu.</B>

<P>Apparently the CIA has gathered intelligence about the possible
involvement of Iranian authorities in the bombing of the TWA 800 plane. 
The gathered material is "vague, nothing solid."  There are also reports
that a terrorist was able to enter Israel via an international airline,
went to his hotel, and assembled a bomb that went off prematurely,
blowing his legs and an arm off.  His intention was to assemble the bomb
and then somehow get it on an airplane that would be leaving from
Israel's Ben Gurion airport.</P>

<P>A draft report by the staff of the House National Security Committee
states that "U.S. intelligence operations were unprepared to deal with
the threat posed to Americans in Saudi Arabia."  Kenneth Bacon gave
details about efforts to improve security before and after the bombing
of the U.S. military housing complex.  Why details about improvements
before the bombing ?  Whatever happened to all the reports, findings,
recommendations, suggestions, changes in policy and procedures that were
or were going to be implemented after the Marine barracks bombing in
Beirut ?</P>  

<P>A journalist pretending to be disabled, hid a toy gun and a fake bomb
in the wheelchair he was using and smuggled them through French and
Israeli airports.</P>  

<P>The one really disturbing fact is that it seems like every single
country just accepted the fact that terrorism is here and here to stay. 
It is even more disturbing to see that all we are able or willing to do
is to build thicker walls, higher walls or wider walls.  Why is it that
democracies adopt such a defeatists attitude ?  We reduced ourselves to
defenders,  to countries who wait to be bombed and terrorized and once
when a building is leveled, we count the bodies, then rebuild it all but
only higher than the previous structure.  Then we wait again and so on. 
We do not dare to punish the ones who are responsible for the mayhem. 
We do not dare to insult or even  worse, accuse any individual culprit,
let alone country or countries.  The prime example is the Pan AM 103
bombing.  Everyone knows who did it, authorities even have their
pictures but what is DONE about it ?  Sure we have filled whole
bookcases with books and reports on it.  Action or Justice ?  None.</P>

<P>Punishment may not be the ideal solution to a problem person but at
least it does two good things.  First it prevents that person from
harming other people again and secondly it sends a message to other
citizens telling them to behave or otherwise they will end up in
prison.  At least that is what it is supposed to do.  I am no longer
sure if today that message is still being sent.  People today do not go
to college because they either do not have the time or because they
cannot afford it.  Great was my surprise when I learned that convicts
could leave prison with a degree !  Why is it that we allow those things
to happen ?  Why is it that the "wrong-doers" are better taken care off
than the "right-doers ?"</P>  

<P>Russian revolutionaries always said that terror had to be done. 
Talking about it was not going to change anything.  Maybe it is time
that governments around the world take that free advise, turn it around,
use it to their advantage and for once do something about this growing
problem terrorism is.</P>
<A NAME="dict"></A>
<P><B>4. Words, words, words.</B>

<P>Another big point of discussion are definitions.  If one looks up the
word <A HREF="#Point3">"terrorize"</A> it says <BR>"1. To fill or
overpower with terror; terrify. <BR>2. To coerce by intimidation or
fear." <BR> If that is the case, then drug dealers, gang members and
mobsters should also be considered terrorists and should be dealt with
accordingly.  It is incomprehensible why so much is written about the
"people" who blow up planes and kill innocent civilians indiscriminately
for political or religious reasons.  Gang members and drug dealers
destroy the future of society: they slowly but surely poison and kill
the children and terrorize the ones who "say no" or stand up against
them.  The teachers, parents, law enforcement officials, reporters and
anyone who is against their "business" can expect harm.  This is
terrorism in its purest form and should at least get as much attention
as the above mentioned form of terrorism.  That is what also should get
national attention, that is what also should become a national priority,
that is what people also should be really concerned about. </P> 

<P>The final word goes to U.S. Senator John Glenn who stated: "I believe
we're into a different type of warfare internationally than we've ever
known before.  I don't think we've learned yet how to deal with this." 
The author is not sure if terrorism is warfare but he agrees 100 % with
the second part of the statement.</P>

<P>On several occasions, people have asked for results in the fight
against terrorism.  The usual answer is: "There are results, but for
security reasons we cannot talk about it."  Or another popular one is:
"It would reveal intelligence methods of operations and sources,
therefore we cannot elaborate but there really are results."  Or "The
case is still under investigation." or just plain "I am not allowed to
talk about it."</P> <BR> 


<A NAME="Point1"></A><BR>
<B>Bombing of U.S. troops in Saudi Arabia</B><BR>
<P>On June 25, 1996 the bombing of the Khobar Tower outside Dhahran in
Saudi Arabia resulted in the loss of nineteen servicemen and injured
about 300.  The device left a crater 30 feet deep and 80 feet  wide. 
All the victims were members of the Air Force.  On 13 November 1995,
another car bomb 
exploded at the U.S.-run military headquarters in the capital of Saudi
Arabia.  That attack killed five Americans and two Indians.  
The attack was claimed by two unknown groups.  The first one is the 
"Legion of the Martyr Abdullah al-Hufaizi" and the second unknown group
calling itself "Hezbollah-Gulf."  

<P>The death toll in Dhahran made it the worst terrorist attack involving
Americans in the Middle East since the bombing in Beirut, Lebanon.  That
bomb killed 241 Americans. </P>

<BR>
<br><center><a href="#arabia">Back to article</a></center>
<hr align=center width=80%>

<A NAME="Point2"></A>
<B>PanAm 103</B><BR>
<P>Four days before Christmas 1988, a  Pan Am Boeing 747, Flight 103,
bound for New York, exploded in midair over Lockerbie, Scotland killing
all 259 passengers and crew.  Two Libyans are suspected.
<br><center><a href="#panam">Back to article</a></center>

<BR><BR>
<hr align=center width=80%>
<A NAME="Point3"></A>
<B>Terrorize</B><BR>
<P>The American Heritage   Dictionary of the English Language, Third
Edition  1992 Houghton Mifflin Co. Electronic Version lic'd from and
portions  1994 InfoSoft Int'l ,Inc.  All rts rsvd.</P>

About the Author:<BR>

<P>Mr. Dermaut, a veteran K-9 officer with the Police in Brussels, Belgium
served also in the military with the Combat Engineers in Germany.  
After about five years he left his law enforcement position to work in
the capacity of personal bodyguard of the American ambassador in Belgium
for the US Department of State where he contracted for this and other
services.  He protected the ambassador and his family in Belgium and
surrounding countries which were high risk areas, having all had local
and international terrorist groups operating internally.  Another task
that was bestowed upon him was the training of both the security force,
which consisted of seventy guards, and a dozen bodyguards.  Mr. Dermaut
also planned, organized, structured and supervised several VIP events
and seminars on antiterrorism and VIP Protection.  

<P>While he was in Kinshasa, Zaire where he worked as Property Management
Supervisor for the US Department of State, he received a  Meritorious
Honor Award for managing a $10 million property inventory and  65
employees.  At present time Mr. Dermaut is a Training Associate and
co-developer of the popular Fail-Safe firearms training concept at the
Global Security Complex. He is also Director of the International
Network of Protection Specialists, a security consultant, published
author and sought after radio and TV authority on the subject of
terrorism.</P>
<BR>
Mr Dermaut may be reached at dermaut@lightspeed.net<BR>
