<td valign=middle width=440>
<center><h2>


</h2>


</Center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>


<H2><Center>Cyber-Civil Disobedience:</H2>
<H4>	Political Dissent in the 90's</H4>
	by Winn Schwartau</Center><BR>

While speaking to 800 raving New York hackers I made what I considered at the time to be an innocuous off-hand comment:<P>

"If my generation had had the technical toys you guys have, the '80's never would have happened."   Then I got to thinking about what I had said.<P>

Twenty five years ago, millions of Americans shouted their anti- government convictions and anti-war sentiments by marching in the streets and engaging in variously creative forms of civil disobedience.  Anti-nuclear activists and environmentalists have maintained the tradition over the years while repeat offender anti- abortionists seemingly wear the badge of both misdemeanors and murder arrests with pride.  But the visceral images of huge traffic-jamming Vietnam era protests broadcast live on the evening news will be the ones indelibly etched in our minds and history books. <P>

Twenty-five years later, due to ever unpopular government stances as it promotes the National Information Infrastructure, the Clinton Administration similarly invites demonstrable outcries, but with the modern twist of technology driven protest.  <P>

In April of 1993 the White House announced the Clipper Chip: perhaps the most loathed invention the US Government has ever sprung upon the American public.  Ostensibly designed to protect telephone conversations from interception with government quality encryption, the NSA designed Clipper is outfitted with a 'back- door' to allow law enforcement to listen in on the encoded signals when approved by the courts.  Outside of a small handful of vocal adherents, Clipper is viewed by its critics (darn close to 100% of the population) as anything from silly and stupid, to technically flawed, to evidence of the totalitarian tendencies of government.  <P>

Despite the continuing outpouring of hatred for the ill-conceived and unworkable Clipper Initiative, the White House continually reaffirmed its support for the 'voluntary' initiative. The IRS has reportedly considered that electronically filed tax returns should be Clipper'd, and that sounds like anything but voluntary.  <P>

The hotly debated Digital Telephony Bill which was passed in late 1994 further exacerbates an already disgruntled cyber-public.  Law enforcement wants to continue its court authorized surveillance activities despite, critics say, no proven need for expensive and possibly invasive anti-privacy technology and legislation.   <P>

Arrogant export control laws turn software programmers into seditious felons if their creations find resting places on overseas hard disks.  A book about cryptography containing source code is freely sold globally, yet an electronic diskette version of the same material is banned from export - even to friendly countries.  Where's the sense?  DES - the Data Encryption Standard - is public domain in the US, and about 50% of the world's DES cryptographic products are not American made. This travesty underscores the inanity of the current policies which cost American business several hundreds of millions of dollars (and jobs) in lost export sales. <P>

The Administration's man-handling of  Cyberspace is deeply questioned and often criticized from the board room to the university to millions of on-line Compuserve and Prodigy and Internet users.  "Don't they get it?"  There is no shortage of critics who feel that the government's attempts at regulating the anarchistic freedoms of the Electronic Superhighway through legislative mandates and policy directives is a poorly disguised shroud.  The fancified term 'National Information Infrastructure' does not settle the stomach of those who swear three ways from Sunday that all the Feds want is to take over Cyberspace on their terms - the people be damned.  Right or wrong, perceptions are the driving force in political dissent.<P>

We also saw a California couple prosecuted in Tennessee for violation of Tennessee pornography laws which bodes fear and loathing when on-line citizens do not truly know with whom they are chatting or where they reside.  Cyber-entrapment comes to mind.  When President Clinton's conceptually endorsed an electronic National ID Card, that too, aroused additional discontent. <P>
 <P>
Twenty five years ago it can't be said that any single event formed the critical mass of dissatisfaction with government policies, nor can it be said today that any single act will trigger similar unrest.  What can be said though, is that the form of protest will not likely resemble any protests of the past.<P>

Cyber-civil Disobedience is timely, poignant and potentially highly effective.<P>

Twenty five years ago, youthful and academic demographics flavored the anti-War movement: predictable looking people predictably demonstrating against government polices while always aware the TV cameras were rolling.  Today, Administration policies are held suspect by a wide cross section of America that crosses most social, economic and age barriers.  <P>
 <P>
Twenty five years ago a demonstration or protest required massive organization and the physical congregation of huge numbers of people, all within the limits of the necessary police permit. Signs and slogans and chants prefaced the occasional Mayor Daly- like headline grabbing over-reactions.  Today, the nether world of Cyberspace offers an unrestricted, unregulated and certainly unorganized refuse as a '90's alternative to conventional assembly. Cyberspace provides the ideal mechanism for Cyber-civil Disobedience, the protest means of choice for the Information Age.  Cyber-civil Disobedience  is waged by remote control, over vast distances, yet can be effectively aimed at selected targets located anywhere.<P>

And, best yet for the Cyber-civil disobedient, there isn't a policeman guarding each and every portal to the information superhighway waiting to haul him off to the slammer.<P>

But Phil Zimmerman,  would probably disagree.  Facing the potential of years in prison, he has been under investigation for violating US export control laws which govern encryption schemes.  Someone, in an apparent act of Cyber-civil disobedience, placed an electronic copy of Phil's PGP (Pretty Good Privacy) software encryption program on the Internet, resulting now in near universal availability of  a very strong encoding method.  Governments, notably ours, aren't happy and want to put a stop to copy cat 'crimes'. <P>

One widely discussed act of mass Cyber-civil Disobedience would be the intentional violation of encryption export laws by tens or hundreds of thousands of people, rendering attempted export policy enforcement virtually impotent.  All that is necessary is to make a copy of a favorite encryption scheme and place it on the 'Net, electronically mail it to their buddies overseas or even just post it on a domestic BBS.  All of these act are, depending upon your interpretation, against the law.  Precedent setting Cyber-civil Disobedience on this scale gives the government the unenviable and unpopular choice of either selective enforcement or policy revision.  <P>

Cyber-civil Disobedience is easily disguised.  If, for example,  the electronic mail boxes of selected, and presumably offensive government services are overloaded with lengthy unnecessary garbage laden messages,  they literally collapse under the weight of popular opinion.  Endless 'pinging' of Internet sites shuts down not only the target but also the benign service provider.  <P>
Such wide spread shrapnelling of targeted systems by millions of Cyber-civil disobedients could effectively shut down non-critical electronic government services whose demise would serve as highly visible media-magnets.  Cyber-events are news and news spreads the word: the protesters need the publicity for enlistment of more sympathizers. <P>

Rotary dial telephones that once used to ring in one's opinion are today replaced with millions of  home PC's connected to millions of modems.  Using a piece of software known as an auto- dialer,  it would only take a few thousand distant and invisible confederates to shut down a company's or agency's PBX, or even PRESIDENT@WHITEHOUSE.GOV and thus their ability to communicate.  With a larger 'demonstration' of Cyber-civil Disobedience, entire telephone exchanges would only be capable of responding to would be callers with, "All Circuits Are Busy."<P>

With an electronic US population of an estimated 20 million, a high percentage of which are Cyber-aware, the capability for Cyber-civil disobedience is within the realm of short term possibility, if not probability.  Network systems have limited bandwidth; an obvious weak point that a Cyber-civil disobedient can easily exploit to the detriment of the service provider and its customers. <P>

But Cyber-civil Disobedience does not necessarily have to be aimed at government. Politically incorrect organizations or companies who say or do the 'wrong' thing, can just as easily be victimized by the same methods.  The Internet Liberation Front launched what it called the first of many attacks against those companies who are commercializing the 'Net.   <P>

Whether it's Right to Lifers shutting down an abortion clinic's ability to communicate or extreme environmentalists striking at a paper mill's piece of Cyberspace instead of the woods, or an angry public venting electronic frustration at an oil-spilling oil company, the capability for Cyber-civil Disobedience is real, and within the power of millions of people. <P>

The 1990 movie, <I>Flashback</I>, concludes with captured '60's radical-activist-hippy Dennis Hopper forewarning FBI agent Keifer Sutherland: <I>"Kid. The 90's are going to make the 60's look like the 50's."</I>  <P>

Washington should keep in mind that for an Information Age population to voice its discontent, America doesn't have to take to the streets.<P>

[This article was first written in October of 1994 and it took 6 months to find a publisher willing to print it; Information Week, March 1995. The first Cyber-civil revolts began in November of that year in France. For more information, see <a href="/winn/ssiw2.html-ssi">Information Warfare: 2nd. Edition</a>]<P>


<BR>

</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
