<td valign=middle width=440>
<center><h3>
Denial of Service on the Internet:<BR> A data dump on the SYN attack.

</h3>


</Center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>

06 November 1996

<P>We first wrote about Denial of Service attacks back in late 1994 and nobody believed it possible. Then it started happening. Now it's getting famous. Here's the complete lowdown on SYN attacks and other Net based DOS. (Longish: 48K)<BR>



FROM:	Dale Drew, INTERNET:ddrew@mci.net<BR>
DATE:	17/9/96, 19:10 <BR>
Date: Tue, 17 Sep 1996 18:51:28 -0400<BR>
To: meals@mci.net<BR>
From: Dale Drew <ddrew@mci.net><BR>
Subject: Cisco; Denial of Service protections :<BR>
  iMCISE:IMCI:091796:01:P1R1<BR>
<BR>
Report Reference: http://www.security.mci.net<BR>
     White Paper: Potential Denial<BR>
     of Service Attacks at Internet<BR>
     Service 	Providers (ISPs)<BR>

      <B>ABSTRAC</B>T<BR>

<P>There are two types of potential denial of service attacks at internet
service providers (ISPs) that are targeted at end hosts and routers.

<P> 	TCP SYN attack: A sender transmits a volume of connections that cannot
be completed. This causes the connection queues to fill up,therby denying
service to legitimate TCP users.

<P>  	UDP diagnostic port attack: A sender transmits a volume of requests=
for UDP diagnostic services on the router which causes all CPU resources to be
consumed servicing the phony requests.

<P>This paper contains a technical description of the potential attacks and
methods for using the Cisco IOS to defend against them.

<P><B>PROBLEM DESCRIPTIONS</B>
<P>The TCP SYN attack:

<P>When a normal TCP connection starts, a destination host receives a SYN
(synchronize/start) packet from a source host and sends back a SYN ACK
(synchronize acknowledge). The destination host must hear an ACK of the SYN
ACK, and then the connection is established. This is referred to as the "TCP
three-way handshake."

<P>While waiting for the ACK to the SYN ACK, a connection queue of finite size
on the destination host keeps track of connections waiting to be completed.
This queue typically empties quickly since the ACK usually arrives a few
milliseconds after the SYN ACK.

<P>The TCP SYN attack exploits this design by having an attacking source host
generate TCP SYN packets with random source addresses at a victim host. The
victim destination host sends a SYN ACK back to the random source address
and adds an entry to the connection queue. Since the SYN ACK is destined for
an incorrect or non-existent host, the last part of the "three-way
handshake" is never completed and the entry remains in the connection queue
until a timer expires, typically for about one minute. By generating phony
TCP SYN packets from random IP addresses at a rapid rate, it is possible to
fill up the connection queue and deny TCP services to legitimate users.

<P>There is no easy way to trace the originator of the attack because the IP
address of the source is phony.

<P>The external manifestations of the problem include inability to get mail,
inability to attach to WWW services, or a large number of TCP connections on
your host in the state SYN_RCVD.

<P>The UDP diagnostic port attack:

<P>By default, the Cisco router has a series of diagnostic ports enabled for
certain UDP and TCP services including echo, chargen, and discard. When a
host attaches to those ports, a small amount of CPU is consumed to service
these requests.

<P>If a single attacking device sends a large barrage of requests with
different, random phony source IP addresses, it is possible that the Cisco
router can become overwhelmed and slow down or fail.  

<P>The external manifestation of the problem includes a process table full
error message (%SYS-3-NOPROC) or a very high CPU utilization. The exec
command show process will show a lot of processes with the same name, for
example, "UDP Echo."

<P><B>DEFENDING AGAINST ATTACKS DIRECTLY TO THE ROUTER</B>

<P>Disabling UDP Diagnostic Ports
<P>Any router not already protected behind a firewall or not using the small
servers (diagnostic services) should disable UCP and TCP diagnostic
services. This can be accomplished by using the global configuration=
 commands:</P>

no service udp-small-servers<BR>
no service tcp-small-servers<BR>

<P>See the appendix for further information on these commands.
Discarding Packets from Unfriendly Source Addresses

<P>Both the TCP SYN attack and UDP diagnostic port attack are characterized by
an influx of packets from random source addresses. One defense for both
types of attacks against the router is to program the router to only allow
packets from "friendly" source addresses on interfaces that are exposed to
the Internet or other unsecured locations. This provides a defense against
random attacks, but still leaves a vulnerability to targeted attacks by
hackers who know "trusted" addresses. Another variation of this defense is
to deny all packets destined to the routers address on exposed interfaces.
The latter defense is possible only if no dynamic routing protocols are
employed.

<P>Example: If interface Serial 0/1 were facing the Internet with an address
of 172.16.10.13, and had BGP peers with addresses 172.16.10.23 and
172.16.10.66, the following configuration would deny all packets from any
other address:</P>
<BR>
	interface serial 0/1<BR>
	ip address 172.16.10.13<BR>
	ip access-group 103 in<BR>
<BR>
	access-list 103 permit ip 172.16.10.23 0.0.0.0 172.16.10.13 0.0.0.0<BR>
	access-list 103 permit ip 172.16.10.66 0.0.0.0 172.16.10.13 0.0.0.0<BR>
	access-list 103 deny ip any 172.16.10.13 0.0.0.0 log *<BR>
        access-list 103 permit ip any any<BR>

<P>*Note: the log option is only needed if tracking of source addresses
attempting to access the router is desired.

<P><B>DEFENDING AGAINST ATTACKS TO HOSTS</B>

<P>Defending against attacks to hosts is a more difficult undertaking.
Filtering on routers is simple since only a few select hosts should be
accessing the router. However, in the case of a web server or mail server
facing the Internet, there is no way to determine which addresses are
legitimate. Therefore, there is no clear cut defense against such an attack.
Several options are available to hosts. You can:</P>

  	Increase the size of the connection queue (SYN ACK queue).<BR>
  	Decrease the time-out waiting for the three-way handshake.<BR>
  	Employ vendor software patches to detect and circumvent the problem (if
        available).<BR>

<P>You should contact your host vendor to see if they have created specific
patches to address the TCP SYN ACK attack.

<P>Filtering is ineffective since the IP addresses vary, and may or may not be
addresses of legitimate hosts.

<P><B>PREVENTING THE NETWORK FROM UNWITTINGLY HOSTING AN ATTACK</B>

<P>Since a primary mechanism of denial of service attacks is the generation of
traffic sourced from random IP addresses, we recommend filtering traffic
destined for the Internet. The basic concept is to throw away packets with
invalid source IP addresses as they enter the Internet. This does not
prevent the denial of service attack on your network, but will help attacked
parties rule out your location as the source of the attacker. In addition,
it prevents the use of your network for this class of attacks.

<P>Preventing Transmission of Invalid IP Addresses

<P>By filtering packets on your routers that connect your network to the
Internet, you can permit only packets with valid source IP addresses to
leave your network and get into the Internet.

<P>For example, if your network consists of network 172.16.0.0, and your
router connects to your ISP using a FDDI0/1 interface, you can apply the
access-list as follows:</P>
<PRE>
  access-list 111 permit ip 172.16.0.0 0.0.255.255 any
  access-list 111 deny ip any any log *

  interface Fddi 0/1
  ip access-group 111 out
</PRE>
<P>* Note: The last line of the access-list determines if there is any traffic
with an invalid source address entering the Internet. It is not crucial to
have this line, but it will help locating the source of the possible attacks.

<P>Preventing Reception of Invalid IP Addresses

<P>For ISPs who provide service to end networks, we highly recommend that you
validate incoming packets from your clients. This means that you will have
to use inbound packet filters on your border routers. This can be done by
using an incoming access-list.

<P>For example, if your clients have the following network numbers connected
to your router via a FDDI interface named "FDDI 1/0", you can create the
following access-list:

<P>The network numbers are 192.168.0.0 to 192.168.15.0, and 172.18.0.0</P>
<PRE>
   access-list 111 permit ip 192.168.0.0 0.0.15.255 any
   access-list 111 permit ip 172.18.0.0 0.0.255.255 any
   access-list 111 deny ip any any log

   interface Fddi 1/0
   ip access-group 111 in
</PRE>
<P>Note: The last line of the access-list determines if there is any traffic
with invalid source address entering the Internet. It is not crucial to have
this line, but it will help locate the source of the possible attack.=20

<P><B>FURTHER READING</B>

<P>This topic has been discussed in some detail on the NANOG [North American
Network Operator's Group] mailing list. The list archives are located at:
http://www.merit.edu/mail.archives/html/nanog/

<P>For a detailed description of the TCP SYN denial of service attack and IP
spoofing, see: http://www.fc.net/phrack/files/p48/p48-13.html
http://www.fc.net/phrack/files/p48/p48-14.html

<P>Also, Steve Bellovin at AT&T has written two technical security papers
which discuss similar attacks in more detail:

<P>ftp://ftp.research.att.com/dist/internet_security/117.ps.Z
<P>ftp://ftp.research.att.com/dist/internet_security/ipext.ps.Z


<P><B>APPENDIX: DESCRIPTION OF SMALL SERVERS</B>

<P>The small servers are servers (daemons, in Unix parlance) running in the
router which are useful for diagnostics. Therefore, they are on by default.

<P>The commands for the TCP and UDP small servers are:</P>

service tcp-small-servers<BR>
service udp-small-servers<BR>

<P>If you do not want your router to provide any non-routing services, you can
turn them off (using the no form of the above commands).

<P>The TCP small servers are:

  	<P>Echo: Echoes back whatever you type. Type the command telnet x.x.x.x
        echo to see.
  	<P>Chargen: Generates a stream of ASCII data. Type the command telnet
        x.x.x.x chargen to see.
  	<P>Discard: Throws away whatever you type. Type the command telnet x.x.x.x
        discard to see.
  	<P>Daytime: Returns system date and time, if correct. It is correct if you
        are running NTP or have set the date and time manually from the exec
level.


<P>Type the command telnet x.x.x.x daytime to see.

<P>The UDP small servers are:</P>

  	Echo: Echoes the payload of the datagram you send.<BR>
  	Discard: Silently pitches the datagram you send.<BR>
  	Chargen: Pitches the datagram you send and responds with a 72 character
        string of ASCII characters terminated with a CR+LF.<BR>

<P>Notes:

       <P>Almost all UNIX boxes support the small servers listed above.
       The router also offers finger service and async line bootp service,
       which can be independently turned off with the configuration global 
       commands "no service finger" and "no ip bootp server", respectively.



     <P>  Other protective measures would include using ACLs to restrict
       SNMP access to the router itself, and disabling SNMP WRITE access -
       as its UDP based and can be spoofed easily.  ACLs should also be
       deployed to protect TELNET access to the routers VTYs, and it is
       recommended to use an enhanced authentication protocal, like XTACACS
       or TACACS+, to authenticate individual users, rather than just a
password.

  <P>     In addition, it is also advisable to make use of the "service config-
       encryption" to protect passwords stored in the router configuration.</P>



<HR>

Dale Drew    MCI Telecommunications<BR>
Sr. Manager    internetMCI Security Engineering<BR>
Voice:  703/715-7058 Internet: ddrew@mci.net<BR>
Fax:    703/715-7066       MCIMAIL: Dale_Drew/644-3335<BR>
<BR>

	----- Forwarded Message -----<BR>
<BR>
TO:	[unknown], INTERNET:NSA@ISS.NET<BR>
FROM:	Christopher Klaus, INTERNET:cklaus@iss.net<BR>
DATE:	9/13/96, 12:03 PM<BR>
<BR>
Re:	[NSA] SYN Flooding [info]<BR>
<BR>
<P>[Below we have a software tool that will recognize SYN floods and correct
the problem.]

<P><B>Possible solution to SYN Flooding attacks</B>


<P>The attack is on!  Both 2600 and Phrack, 2 of the biggest well-known
underground hacking magazines, have posted exploit code to do one of the
nastiest denial of service attacks that the Internet has seen so far. 
Hundreds of people have access to these programs to bring down services on
the Internet.  Many of these people are targeting their attacks at various
organizations such as ISP.  Panix, an ISP, has been under attack for quite
a few days now and they have not been able to receive email. Many other
ISPs are suffering from the SYN flood attack.  This attack is being
discussed on many mailing lists, newsgroups, and Thursday's Wall Street
Journal (9/12/96).  Fortunately a solution already exists as we discuss
below.

<P>Everyone connected to the Internet relies on TCP/IP.  When you establish a
connection with TCP, you do a 3-way handshake.  The connecting host sends
a SYN packet to the receiving host.  The receiving host sends a SYN|ACK
packet back and to fully establish a connection, the connecting host
finally responds with an ACK packet. 

<P>In a SYN flood attack, an attacker host sends many SYN packets and does
not respond with an ACK to the SYN|ACK's.  As the receiving host is
waiting for more and more ACK's, the buffer queue will fill up and the
receiving machine can no longer accepts legitimate connections. This means
that attackers can block your email, web, or any other service you are
providing on the Internet. 

<P>To even make this attack worse, the code exploiting the problem randomizes
the source address of the attacking host.  Thus, the receiving machine
gets packets that appear to be from all over the Internet, hiding the
location of the attacker. 

<P><B>Solution</B>

<P>There are several things we can do to stop these attacks from being
effective. 

<P>With the routers for most ISP, they should be blocking any non-internal
addresses from leaving their network and going to the Internet. This will
stop an attacker if their ISP implements this.  Unfortunately, this does
not stop an attack from areas on the Internet that do not block that. But
at least the ISP can feel comfortable to know that an attacker can not
launch his attack from that ISP. 

<P>Here are two methods of helping eliminate the problem.  Some of the
exploit code I have seen does not pick a random source port.  It would be
easy to block the attack with a router denying any packets coming from a
specific source port. This may not be too effective because of the trivial
nature of adding code to randomize the source port, sequence number,
source address, and TTL.  But it might help you temporarily if you notice
the attacks have any pattern that can be blocked by router rules. 

<P>Another way to fix this is to set the kernel maximum number of half open
connections allowed (SO_MAXCONN) to a higher number than the default value.
We have a tool that will look for SYN packets that do not get followed with
ACK and clean the half open connections by sending a RST packet.  This 
unclogs the port and allows legitimate connections to happen.  This tool
is called RealSecure (tm).  To obtain a copy of the RealSecure tool,
send email to majordomo@Iss.net and within the body of the message, type: 

<P>	subscribe realsecure

<P>RealSecure (tm) is a comprehensive attack recognition and real time response
tool that ISS is alpha testing and will expire in 60 days.</P>

-- 
Christopher William Klaus	     Voice: (770)395-0150. Fax: (770)395-1972<BR>
Internet Security Systems, Inc.     "Internet Scanner finds<BR>
Ste. 660,41 Perimeter Center East,Atlanta,GA 30346 your network security holes<BR>
Web: http://www.iss.net/  Email: cklaus@iss.net        before the hackers do."<BR>
<BR>
<CENTER>		 Savvy Hacker Tangles         Web For Net Host</CENTER>
<BR>
Dow Jones  9/12/96  6:01 AM<BR>
<BR>
   By Bart Ziegler<BR>
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal<BR>
<P> A pioneering Internet-access provider that hosts almost a thousand corporate
Web sites has been virtually shut down since late last week by a computer hacker
bombarding the service's computers with requests to send information.
<P>  The attacks, which have lasted more than a day at a time, have rendered almost
defenseless the small New York company, Public Access Networks Corp., or Panix.
They also underscore a key vulnerability of the Internet. "This is the first
major attack of a kind that I believe to be the final Internet security
problem," says William Cheswick, an Internet security expert at the Bell
Laboratories unit of Lucent Technologies Inc. "We're going to see a lot more of
this," he predicts.
<P>  The hacker invasion began late Friday afternoon and went on almost constantly
through Sunday afternoon. Then it mysteriously subsided -- only to resume in the
predawn hours of Monday morning. The attacks, which were still continuing
yesterday, forced shutdowns that let up only intermittently, and even then only
because the hacker temporarily halted his efforts.
<P>  "We could be out of business a week from now if this keeps up -- there's no
way to fight it," says Alexis Rosen, co-founder and majority owner of the
closely held company.
<P>  Among the Web sites Panix hosts are those of the Wilhelmina modeling agency,
the Miss America pageant and a Mercedes dealer network. The unknown intruder has
alternately invaded Panix computers that control pages on the World Wide Web,
others that store electronic-mail, and still other machines that link Internet
addresses to Panix subscribers, blocking them from receiving any communications.
<P>  In effect, the hacker's method is similar to campaigns used by some activist
groups to flood a politician's switchboard with phone calls. So much time is
spent sorting out the bogus calls -- in this case, the hacker's false requests
for an electronic "handshake" with Panix machines -- that the legitimate ones
can't get through.
<P>  The hacker has been sending up to 150 requests a second to Panix's computers,
seeking to establish a connection to send or receive information. The requests,
presumably generated by a malicious computer program, contain fake Internet
addresses, which Panix's computers must sort out before they can discard them.
The computers have choked under the deluge, preventing them from handling
legitimate requests from Internet users for access to the World Wide Web sites
that Panix hosts or to send electronic mail to Panix's more than 6,000
individual users.
<P>  Panix is trying to find the source of the attack by working backward through
the labyrinthine network of phone lines and specialized "router" computers that
form the Internet. But Mr. Rosen and Mr. Cheswick say there is no easy way to
trace such hackers.
<P>  "This is new enough, and the technical expertise is scarce enough, that it is
going to be hard to muster [the resources to do tracing] for a while," says Mr.
Cheswick, who is on-site at Panix's Manhattan offices trying to help fix the
trouble.
 <P> As to who might be targeting Panix, the firm's Mr. Rosen speculated it could
be someone upset by the fact that the company hosts, free, the Web site of
Voters Telecommunications Watch, a group that advocates free speech on the
Internet. "We've always tried to lead the way to being a good citizen on the Net
and there are people who don't like that," Mr. Rosen says. On the other hand,
says Bell Labs' Mr. Cheswick, "It could have been a seventh-grader who feels
slighted" by Panix for some reason.</P>
  (END) DOW JONES NEWS 09-12-1996<BR>
   6 00 AM<BR>
<BR>
Copyright 1996 Dow Jones & Co., Inc.  All rights reserved.<BR>

<P>   Three years ago Panix was the victim of another attack when an intruder
obtained high-level electronic access to its computers, forcing the service to
shut down for three days. The invader stole passwords of Panix subscribers that
could be used to gain access to other computer networks.
<P>  Mr. Cheswick says he "has been waiting" for an attack like the current one so
he could study it, since it exploits one of the big remaining holes in Internet
security. In fact, when Mr. Cheswick co-authored a book on Internet security a
few years ago, at the last minute, he says, he removed a section on this type of
assault for fear of tipping off hackers. While there have been a few previous
reports of such incidents, the Panix episode is the most severe, he says.
 <P> Internet computers have no quick way of distinguishing a bogus request for
information from a real one, Mr. Cheswick says. While upgrades to the software
controlling these computers could ease the problem, hackers could respond with
even more intensive attacks.
<P>  "There's going to be the usual arms race" between better security measures and
hackers, Mr. Cheswick predicts.
 
<P>  Journal Link: For the text of e-mail from Panix co-founder Alexis Rosen to
Panix members, see The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition at http://wsj.com</P>
  (END) DOW JONES NEWS 09-12-96<BR>
   6 08 AM<BR>
<BR>
Copyright 1996 Dow Jones & Co., Inc.  All rights reserved.<BR>
[DMK: It's also in Phrack 48]<BR>
	  Whoever Attacked Net Firm    Could Have Found Guide<BR>
<BR>
Dow Jones  9/13/96  6:07 AM<BR>
<BR>
   By Bart Ziegler<BR>
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal<BR>
<P>  NEW YORK -- Where did that computer hacker who virtually shut down an Internet
provider this week get his skills? He might have simply turned to the latest
issue of 2600 magazine, the Hacker Quarterly.
<P>  There, he'd find line-by-line instructions for creating a computer program to
inflict just such damage to an Internet service as experienced by Public Access
Networks Corp., or Panix. "It's very, very, very bad," says the article's
disclaimer -- before giving the directions.
<P>  New York-based Panix was attacked on and off for five days starting last
Friday. The unknown assailant flooded Panix's computers with requests to start
transmissions to them, a strategy that overloaded the machines and prevented
legitimate requests from getting through.
<P>  Emmanuel Goldstein, 2600's editor, defends the article as a way to point out
holes in computer security that need to be fixed. He says similar attacks have
occurred before, and that he's not even sure the hacker who attacked Panix used
2600 as a guide, since an on-line publication recently published similar
directions.
 <P> "We need to educate the community that it's very, very simple to cause massive
mayhem," says Mr. Goldstein, who publishes the magazine in Setauket, N.Y. "A lot
of companies subscribe to us so they can learn before they're victimized."
<P>  The magazine, sold in major bookstore chains, contains articles on how to use
pay phones without paying, how to get a phone line under a fake name and how to
capture computer passwords to break into systems, among others. (The magazine's
name refers to the frequency, in hertz, of a whistle that phone "phreaks" once
blew to break into phone systems.) But Mr. Goldstein denies that the intent is
to tell people how to break the law or cause damage.
<P>  Alexis Rosen, Panix's co-owner, says he supports what 2600 does even though it
may have led to the attacks that threaten his on-line business. "As a matter of
principle I don't think they [2600] should have been stopped," Mr. Rosen says.
But he adds that unlike almost every other instruction for hacking that 2600 has
published, there is no known technical defense that can be used by the victim.
<P> 2600's tactics, while bold, parallel a "central debate" in the computer
industry over how to respond to security problems, says Doug Tygar, an associate
professor at Carnegie Mellon University's School of Computer Science. "On one
hand there is a point of view that you should disclose the information as widely
as possible because that's the fastest way of getting it fixed," he says. "The
other point of view is you should put a lid on it" to limit copycats.</P>
  (END) DOW JONES NEWS 09-13-96<BR>
   6 00 AM<BR>
<BR>
Copyright 1996 Dow Jones & Co., Inc.  All rights reserved.<BR>
<BR>


<P>Copyright 1996 The Associated Press. All rights reserved.@bThe information
contained in this news report may not be published, broadcast or otherwise
distributed without the prior written authority of the Associated Press.</P>
  
By EVAN RAMSTAD<BR>
 AP Business Writer<BR>
<P>   NEW YORK (AP) -- An unscrupulous computer hacker, taking
advantage of a weakness in the construction of the Internet, has
essentially shut down an online company by bombarding it with
scores of bogus queries every second.
<P>  For nearly a week, thousands of individual and corporate
customers have been unable to log on to the worldwide computer
network using Public Access Networks Corp., New York City's first
Internet access provider.
 <P>  The small, privately owned company, known as Panix, says it may
not survive if the attack persists.
 <P>  "It means 25 people could shortly be looking for work," said
Alexis Rosen, the company's president and co-owner.
 <P>  The hacker is sending scores of requests for information each
second to computers at Panix. But the requests have fake return
addresses, which confuse the Panix computers. At the rate the fake
requests are coming, Panix is unable to handle legitimate
interactions with other computers.
 <P>  Security experts say it is one of the longest such attacks ever
seen, and highlights a problem with the Internet that many network
design engineers are familiar with but rarely discuss publicly.
<P>  Computers that provide information distributed through the
Internet operate under the general assumption that they will be
sending the information to a legitimate destination.
<P>   If the request has a fake destination, the computer becomes tied
up trying to find it. If one is not found the computer moves on to
the next task. Computers are set up to handle only a few bogus
requests simultaneously, not dozens or hundreds per second.
  <P> Experts from Lucent Technologies Inc.'s Bell Labs and the CERT
Coordination Center, a Pittsburgh-based group that responds to
Internet security troubles, are helping Panix.
<P>  But Rosen said, "There's no help to be had. This a problem
fundamental to the structure of the Internet."
<P>   The easiest solution would be for all other Internet access
companies to filter their outgoing traffic to make sure the data
has legitimate return addresses. But it could take months for
companies to agree to that and take the necessary technical steps.
<P>  "Until all people start filtering their traffic to assure there
are no forgeries in the packets, this attack can continue
unabated," Rosen said.
 <P>  "We've been batting around possible defenses," said William
Cheswick, a Bell Labs scientist. But he said any kind of computer
system can be overloaded.
  <P> "It's an arms race," he said. "A lot of the easy solutions
for dealing with the attack are looking for idiosyncrasies in it
and separating the attack (data) packets from the other ones. That
game only goes on for so long before we can't tell them apart
again."
<P>   Typically, hacker attacks on corporate computers are brief. The
length of time Panix has been under siege is especially severe. It
began last Friday, was interrupted Sunday evening but restarted
Monday.
  <P> Panix, started in 1989, has 6,000 individual subscribers and
connects over 1,000 companies to the Internet. It also hosts World
Wide Web sites for dozens of companies.
 <P>  Rosen, the technical wizard behind the service, has had little
sleep since the attacks began. "What else would I be but tired and
angry?"

<P><B>HTML report</B>
<P> Be afraid. Be very afraid. There is
 a new kind of vandalism that exploits
 the very foundation of the Internet.
 Not only is it virtually impossible to
 deflect, it could effectively shut down
 any Internet Service Provider. The
 attack, known as a SYN attack,
 hobbled New York's oldest Internet
 gateway, Public Access Networks
 (Panix.com), for the better part of the
 past week, cutting off access to its
 7,000 subscribers. 

<P>    "This is the easiest and the
 deadliest of all the spoofing attacks
 out there," says Alexis Rosen,
 Panix's cofounder. "Ultimately this
 attack cannot realistically be
 defended against unilaterally." 

<P>     The code for the SYN attack
 became public earlier this summer
 when it was posted on 2600 and
 Phrack sites. This isn't your usual
 Spammy-the-Unamailer-
 I'm-a-kewl-twelve-year-old-dude-and
 know how to send E-mail.But security
 experts such as Bill Cheswick of
 Lucent Technologies have known
 about this Achilles heel and feared
 such an attack for years. Indeed,
 when they were writing their most
 recent book on information security,
 Cheswick and his co-author omitted a
 description of the SYN attack for fear
 of tipping anyone off to it. 

<P>    "We have regretted that act," he
 told The Netly News. "The
 denial-of-service attack is one that is
 possible even after we've fixed every
 security hole you can find on the Net.
 I'd rather the good guys had known
 about this." 

 <P>   SYN takes its name from the initial
 packet that allows two machines to
 negotiate network communication.
 When you fire up a connection, your
 computer sends a SYN
 (synchronization) containing your IP
 address to the server you are trying
 to contact. The remote server then
 returns a SYNACK, or
 synchronization acknowledgement.
 Finally your machine sends back a
 final ACK, or acknowledgement, and
 the connection is established. Rosen
 compares it to a walk in the park
 where someone shouts "Hey you!"
 Not knowing where the shout
 originated, you shout back "Who
 me?" If the person replies, "Yeah,
 you," then you've established
 communication. 

 <P>    The SYN attack is Internet
 schizophrenia. By flooding the pipe
 with shouts, the spoofer creates a
 perpetual state of "Who me?" on the
 victim's server. The code sends out
 random and forged source IP
 addresses at the rate of around 50
 per second. But since the source IP is
 bogus, the victim's server, when it
 sends back a SYNACK, is left
 waiting for a response, creating a
 half-open connection to nowhere that
 lasts on average 75 seconds. Even on
 the best SUN Sparc servers the
 number of simultaneous SYNACKs
 that can be held waiting is fewer than
 10. Once those spots are filled, any
 real user who tries to connect will get
 no response. Nothing but a long wait
 until the computer gives up. 

<P>    "Any ankle biter with a Linux box
 and a modem can just run this code
 and screw things up," says Rosen.
 "When I say anybody, I mean
 anybody." 

<P>     Working around the clock since for
 five straight days, Rosen did develop
 methods to deflect the attack -- with
 plenty of help from friends like
 Cheswick and the dudes who run
 Netaxs in Philadelphia. At first the
 attacker was careless and left
 earmarks on his packets, so Rosen
 created a "kernel hack" that filtered
 out those packets. That didn't last
 long. There are other hacks that
 Rosen plans to make public, but he's
 leery of giving away any information
 that will ultimately help the attacker.
 Especially since every fix that Rosen
 developed, the attacker was
 eventually able to subvert. 

<P>    "There are lots of things you can
 do to mitigate this," says Cheswick.
 However, "Pretty much any move
 you make can be countered once the
 attacker figures out what you've
 done." 

<P>The only real solution that Rosen
     and Cheswick found involves the
     cooperation of every Internet
     Service Provider in the nation. It
     would require each ISP to create a
     database with all its users IP
     addresses. A filter could then be
     created that would allow the
     provider to screen any packets that
     originated from unregistered IP
     sources. But this is a costly fix, and
     it's hard to believe that everyone
     would be willing to comply. Large
     providers could take months to
     implement such filtering, and
     smaller providers risk toasting their
     routers by using such devices. 

<P>         Even then, how would we defend
     from a SYN attack originating in
     China or Finland? The only answer
     would be to "shun" any site that
     didn't comply with the filtering
     process. And then what happens
     when Sprint hooks up a tiny
     mom-and-pop ISP and they forget to
     filter. Suddenly the whole network
     is exposed. 

<P>         Attempts to trace the attacker
     through various routers on the
     network have been unsuccessful.
     Rosen told us that he suspects the
     attacker is using a very slow
     modem that connects to a 56kbs
     line, which is where the packets are
     bottlenecking. Had the attacker
     used a T1 or, God forbid, a T3
     "we'd all be fucked," says Rosen.
     "I would like to think that we are
     sufficiently clever that we will catch
     the guy. And if we do, I can promise
     you that he will pay for it for the
     rest of his life." 

 <P>        This is not the first vicious attack
     that Panix has suffered. The
     service's radical stances on free
     speech and spamming have earned
     them lots of enemies. "Maybe it's
     someone who could care less about
     Net politics," says Shabbir Safdar
     of Voter's Telecommunications
     Watch, whose web site was shut
     down by the attack on the eve of
     important news from Senator John
     Kerry. "I've poked through our
     kook mail from the last few months
     -- we get a lot of it -- and no one
     stands out." 

<P>         Luckily the attacks subsided
     yesterday. Had they continued,
     Rosen says his business might not
     have survived. Cheswick says that
     lawyers and law enforcement
     authorities are likely to become
     very involved in this case, since
     thousands of dollars are now at
     stake. In Cheswick's mind this is
     yet another gloomy beacon of the
     age of information warfare. 

<P>        "In the long run people will get
     more ready," says Cheswick.
     "There are bad things that will
     happen one day. We can only
     postpone them." </P>

     --By Noah Robischon <BR>

Cancel FAQ is www.math.uiuc.edu/~tskirvin/home/cancel.html<BR>
