<IMG ALT="[Bomb2]" SRC="../../images/bomb2_li.gif" width=580><p>


<!-- Article Body Table ---------------------------------------------->

<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<img border=0 width=43 height=43 src="../../images/lock.gif">
</td>
<td valign=middle width=440>
<center><h3>
Ernst & Young/InformationWeek's fourth annual<BR>
Information Security Survey.

</h3>


</Center>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width=440>


NEW YORK-(BUSINESS WIRE)-Oct. 21, 1996<BR>
<P>Lack of confidence in information security, widespread Internet access and increased malicious attacks by insiders have caused significant information security losses at major U.S. companies,
according to the fourth annual Ernst & Young LLP/InformationWeek Information
Security Survey. More than half (54 percent) of the survey's 1,320 participants
experienced losses due to information security and disaster recovery within the
last two years. Adding computer viruses to the mix, the number rose to a
startling 78 percent. Significant losses were caused by malicious acts by
company insiders (32 percent), malicious acts by outsiders (18 percent),
natural
disasters (25 percent) and industrial espionage (six percent). Nearly
three-quarters (71 percent) of the executives surveyed expressed a lack of
confidence in the security of their computer networks, from both internal and
external attack. "The threats can come from an unsecured Internet connection, a
malicious attack by a disgruntled employee, the loss of a laptop with critical
information, industrial espionage or just plain carelessness," said Scott D.
Ramsey, national director of information security, Ernst & Young. "While
companies spend more money on sophisticated computer hardware, they often fail
to devote attention to safeguarding information systems, equipment and the
people who use it." "Information security is undoubtedly one of the biggest
concerns our readers have. The results of this survey not only confirm this but
also serve as a wakeup call that something must be done to make the enterprise
feel more secure," said Charles Pelton, managing editor/industry, CMP Media's
InformationWeek.</P>
Nosing Around on the 'Net<BR>
<P>The survey also uncovered that while most companies are using the Internet or
Intranet for vital business functions, many feel that the information security
measures for both are ineffective. While nearly 40 percent expressed
dissatisfaction with the overall security level of their companies' Internet
connection, less than one-third (31 percent) of the respondents said they could
detect vulnerability to hackers who can dial-in through external Internet
connections. In fact, 25 percent said someone had used the Internet to attempt
to break into their system during the last year. To make matters worse, nearly
three quarters (74 percent) lack a formal incident response team. "As increased
use of outside vendors and contract employees heightens exposure, organizations
must start monitoring the connections between themselves and their service
providers," added Ramsey. "Companies don't realize that the moment they give
computer access to a contractor, they are handing the keys to the kingdom to a
short-term employee." In addition, only a third (34 percent) of the companies
with Internet access are using the connection to perform electronic commerce
transactions, such as financial transactions, and the taking and placing of
product orders, suggesting that companies are proceeding with caution.
Malicious Attacks from Inside Service providers are not the only people who need monitoring, according to the survey findings. Losses due to internal malicious attacks have nearly doubled
since 1995, with corporate downsizing a possible key motivator for these acts.
"Ironically, `compassionate' relocation packages that allow terminated
employees to remain on-site - with access to corporate computer systems - can backfire on
employers," added Ramsey. "Companies must consider the damage that just one
embittered former employee can do to the operations of a company." Six percent
of those surveyed have suspected industrial espionage attacks on their systems.
Ramsey speculates that since the really good spies never get caught, it's hard
to quantify a company's exposure in this area. "Industrial espionage is illegal
in the United States, but not in foreign countries, and we have noted an
increased level of intelligence gathering from overseas," added Ramsey. To
illustrate the severity of security risks, Ernst & Young revealed how it has
embarked on "staged penetrations" and infiltrated corporate offices at the
request of clients. Past penetrations have allowed Ernst & Young
representatives to gain access to their client's e-mail systems, read sensitive data, such as
merger and acquisition material, and walk out the door with $35,000 worth of
laptops and other equipment. "It's a real eye-opener when a CEO receives an
e-mail from a hacker, describing all the confidential information that's been
read," said Ramsey. 
<P>The Ernst & Young/InformationWeek Information Security
Survey surveyed 1,320 chief information officers (CIOs) and other senior
information executives. For immediate access to excerpts of the report, visit
the Ernst & Young Web site at: </P>
<a href="http://www.ey.com/us/isas/survey.html">http://www.ey.com/us/isas/survey.html</a> 
<P>To request a copy of the report, contact
Rita McKinley at 216.737.1288 or via e-mail at rita.mckinley@ey.com.
NOTE: Ernst & Young LLP is the leading integrated professional services firm,
with more than 21,000 people in 90 U.S. locations. The firm's Information
Systems auditing and security professionals provide a broad range of IS
ervices, including assessing information system controls, evaluating and
improving information security, controlling systems under development,
providing
internal audit assistance, computerized data analysis and business continuity
planning. Published weekly by CMP Media Inc., InformationWeek is the premier
source of news, strategies, trends and product and technology information for
people who manage technology in business. Information Week, at rate base of
350,000, has the largest circulation in the information systems category. </P>

<P>CMP's InformationWeek On-line <a href="http://www.informationweek.com">(http://www.informationweek.com)</a> is the electronic
counterpart to InformationWeek.</P>
 
