<tr>
<td width=440>

<h3><Center>THE RUSSIAN MILITARY IN CRISIS ...<BR></H3>
<h4>By Steve Macko, ENN Editor</h4>
<BR>
</Center>

</table>
<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<td width=440>

<BR>



October 28, 1996<BR><BR>

<P>According to a recent study that was conducted for the U.S. Air
Force by the Rand Corporation, Russian air force modernization
is at a standstill and its tactical aircraft inventory has
dropped by more than 50 percent.

<P>The Rand study reported that there was was one single new Russian
combat aircraft budgeted in 1996.  The air force only purchased 23
planes in the combined years of 1993 and 1994.  By comparison,
during the early 1980s, the Soviet Union purchased 400 to 450
aircraft per year.

<P>The study, entitled, "Russia's Air Power at the Crossroads," was
written by veteran analyst Benjamin S. Lambeth.  Lambeth says
that in 1989, the Soviet Union had more than 5,000 combat aircraft.
Today, it has less than half that number.  About one-third of
the available aircraft today are fourth generation MiG-29s and
Su-27s.  The remainder of the air fleet are older aircraft that
are scheduled to be retired by the year 2000.

<P>According to Russian Air Force estimates, if current Russian budget
trends continue, the inventory of tactical aircraft will drop from
2,280 to 1,670 in 1997.  By the year 2000, the fleet will decline
to 1,440.  And by the year 2005, Russia will have 1,330 planes.

<P>The Rand report stated, "Russia face no air-to-air or other
operational challenge today that would even remotely warrant
the expenditure of large amounts of scarce funds on the Russian
Air Force's state need for a new combat fighter.  The main thrust
of Russia's current defense planning is being directed toward
power projection, not high-technology air warfare, as the air
force's recent combat experience in Chechnya has amply attested."

<P>The Rand study added, Russian defense officials' top priority
is transport aircraft.

<P>Lambeth and his study also documented a long list of woes that
have recently become familiar in discussions of the Russian
military.  But in regards to the air force, problems seen include:
<UL>
-- The decline of air defense.  In 1991, at the time of the collapse
of the Soviet Union, the air force had 2,300 intercepters.  Today,
they have less than half that number.<BR>

-- The Russian air force faces a fuel shortage of crisis proportions
and fuel prices continue to increase rapidly.<BR>

-- The pilot-to-aircraft ratio is much too high.  Fighter pilots
are only averaging 25 flying hours per year.<BR>

-- A shortage of spare parts and manpower to maintain aircraft.<BR>
</UL>

<P>On Friday, Russian Defense Minister Igor Rodionov warned that
Russia faces an erosion of its military readiness unless the
decline in the military budget is reversed.  Rodionov was said
to have painted a grave picture of the state of the Russian
military.

<P>The Defense Minister said, "The armed forces are on the edge,
beyond which extremely undesirable and even uncontrollable
events might take place."

<P>In recent years, Russia's spending on defense has fallen sharply.
Rodionov said, "If the 1997 defense budget is not corrected,
Russia might lose its armed forces as integral and capable state
structure."

<P>Since the end of the Cold War, the Russian army's prestige has
also fallen.  It recent battles in Chechnya, the Russian army
was said to have been humiliated by Chechen fighters.

<P>The proposed 1997 budget has earmarked $18.5 billion for defense
spending.  Rodionov says that it will cover about 33 percent of
what the military really needs.  He cited the "decreasing levels
of combat and mobilization readiness."  Rodionov added that
many soldiers and officers have not been paid in months.

<P>The once-feared Russian military has been in retreat since the
breakup of the Soviet Union five years ago.  The army is said
to be short of money and its poorly trained personnel show
little will to fight -- as evidenced by the setbacks it received
on the battlefield in Chechnya.

<P>Rose Gottemoeller, the deputy director of the International
Institute for Strategic Studies in London, said, "The problem
at the moment is the chaotic implosion of the armed forces.
They need to downsize and profesinalize, but it needs to be
a planned and controlled process."

<P>Since the end of the Cold War, the Russian military has
struggled to define a new role for itself.  It lacks both
the resources and a clear foreign enemy.  This lack of
direction is seen as dangerous to some military analysts.

<P>Fortunately, most analysts do not foresee any revolt in the
military.  True, there are some hardliners in the officer
corps who wish for the lost empire of the Soviet era, there
are also many officers who support pro-reform.

<P>The vast majority of the soldiers are conscripts and they only
desire to get out of the military and cannot be counted upon
to back any attempt of a coup.

<P>Retired Lt.-General Mikhail Surkov, the deputy chairman of the
Duma's defense committee, said, "If urgent measures aren't taken,
the state may be left without well-trained military forces.  It's
better to have no armed forces than to have them untrained."

<P>The Russian economy is in crisis.  The armed forces have been
unable to pay many of their officers and men with even decent
rations.  The number of personnel in the military has dropped
from 2.7 million in 1992 to 1.5 million today.  Many analysts
say that number is still too high for what Russia needs.

<P>Defense Minister Rodionov wants to slash 300,000 men from the
ranks.  He also wants to decrease the number of combat divisions
from 78 to 12.  This would allow the Russian Army to be made
truly operational and will allow them to be supplied with more
modern weapons and be trained as truly professional soldiers.

<P>A specialist of the Russian military at Scotland's Edinburgh
University, John Erikson, said, "Russian capability at the
moment consists probably of being able to put one fully equipped
division in the field and to conduct limited operations outside
its borders -- provided it could operate under air superiority."

<P>Taking an even dimmer view of the Russian military is Alexander
Konovalov, who is the director of a military policy center at
Moscow's Institute of USA and Canada.  He says the Russian
military is "definitely not strong enough" to operate outside
of its borders.  But, he added, that is no longer its mission.

<P>In analyzing Defense Minister Rodionov's plans, Konovalov said,
"If he is thinking of reducing the military to twelve divisions,
this is a man who is ready for painful, decisive, responsible
steps."


>>> Continued in Part 2 >>>
</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
