<tr>
<td width=440>

<h3><Center><B>Ft. McClellan General Announces Reserve Bio-War Unit</B><BR></H2>

<BR>
</H3></Center>

</table>
<table width=580 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2 valign=top width=60 align=right>
<td width=440>
<P>
<BR>
<P>According to official reports, the U.S. Army has
announced the activation of the new 310th Chemical Company, a unit
designed to detect biological warfare agents in combat, something that
the Army has acknowledged it could not previously do.

<P>"This is the very first biological detection company in our country,"
according to Maj. Gen. Ralph Wooten, commander of Fort McClellan. "If
necessary, we have a unit that can be immediately deployable." In the
1991 Gulf War the U.S. military found itself facing a foe that had
developed several types of biological weapons.

<P>The military concluded after the Gulf War that Iraq never used any of
the weapons, such as anthrax, but it conceded that it had no way to
effectively detect or defeat biological weapons. "Our Achilles' heel was
biological warfare," Wooten said Saturday.

<P>The 310th Chemical Company, a reserve unit at Fort McClellan, has mobile
biological detection laboratories mounted on reinforced Humvees. Each of
the 35 labs weighs 10,000 pounds and costs taxpayers about $1 million,
officials said.  The on-board "Biological Integrated Defense Systems"
can detect four types of biological agents, although the Army won't
specify which ones.
</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<br>
