<U>Acknowledgments</U>
<P>
 First of all, this paper would not have been possible without
the support of INSS.  I also wish to thank Colonel Carl Reddel,
Professor and Head, USAFA Department of History.  The following
people contributed in some way, either through interviews, e-mails,
phone conversations, &quot;B-S&quot; sessions, and proofreading.
 Without their help, I'd be in serious trouble right now having
a paper to write by the deadline.  They are: From the 34th Education
Group, USAFA -- <B>Major Donna Schutzius and Dolores Karolick
</B>. From the Department of Political Science, USAFA --<B> General
(Ret) James McCarthy.</B> From the 193rd SOW (PA Air Guard) --
<B> Lt Col William Schaetzle</B>. From the US Army War College
-- <B>Dr. Earl Tilford, Jr. and Dr. Douglas Johnson</B>. From
Maxwell AFB -- <B>Colonel (Ret) Richard Szafranski, Dr. George
Stein, Lt. Col. (Ret) Norm Hutcherson, Major Rick Sowell.</B>
From OASD/C3I <B>Colonel (Ret) Douglas Hotard and Captain Richard
O'Neill.</B> From HQ AFROTC --<B> Lt Col Mykel D. Gable</B>. From
the National Defense University -- <B>Dr. Dan Kuehl and Dr. Thomas
Czerwinski.</B> From the Department of History, USAFA a very special
thanks to -- <B>Lt. Col. Pete Faber, Colonel Steve Chiabotti,
Colonel Mark Wells, Major Lorry Fenner, Major Tony Kern, and Major
Jim Simon</B>. I hope I did not forget anybody.  Ultimately, the
views expressed in this paper are my own, and I alone am responsible
for their content.
<P>
<U>Executive Summary</U>
<P>
 This paper answered a question posed by HQ USAF/INXI: What do
Air Force personnel need to learn in order to operate effectively
in an information warfare (IW) environment?  The question asks
for a bridge to the twenty-first century multipolar world. The
author contends that the Air Force will not be adequately configured
to meet the next century until its leaders demand, and pursue,
fundamental restructuring of our educational, training and operational
frameworks. Seventeen specific recommendations are outlined to
show the way toward this goal.
<P>
 This paper challenges the Air Force to seek long-lasting change
by reaching deep into the very soul of the institution and redefining
its <I>core values</I> and <I>core competencies</I>.  Our current
core values of  <I>integrity, service before self, and excellence
in all we do</I> make no mention of warfighting, intellectual
prowess or creativity.  One of our core competencies, <I>information
dominance</I> is unrealistic.  No IW education program ever devised
will achieve it. Rather, we should pursue <I>situational awareness
on a global scale</I> and prepare our personnel to operate effectively
in an environment of uncertainty.  
<P>
 Until these values are changed, no education and training program
-- even those based on the recommendations of this paper -- will
last long enough to ensure victory in the future.  More importantly,
until these values are wholeheartedly <I>embraced</I> by the Air
Force leadership and all Air Force personnel, they will only be
hollow words incapable of preventing institutional fragmentation.
 Therefore, a call to meet the information warfare environment
is truly a call to meet the future as a unified, airminded, Air
Force.
</td>

<td width=80>
<br>
</td>
</tr>
